WEBVTT

00:40.214 --> 00:42.433
[WIND WHISTLING SOFTLY]

00:47.308 --> 00:49.266
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

00:58.623 --> 01:00.799
[UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

01:01.974 --> 01:05.891
MAN: Agatha Christie's
The Mousetrap.

01:05.935 --> 01:11.201
In my opinion, a second-rate
murder mystery.[SCOFFS]

01:11.245 --> 01:13.638
Not that I've seen it,
you understand.

01:13.682 --> 01:15.553
But it's a whodunit.

01:15.597 --> 01:17.729
You've seen one,
you've seen 'em all.

01:20.210 --> 01:21.777
You know the drill.

01:21.820 --> 01:23.387
An interminable prologue

01:23.431 --> 01:26.260
in which
all the key players
are introduced.

01:26.303 --> 01:29.089
You get a sense
of the world they inhabit,

01:29.132 --> 01:32.614
and then
the most unlikable character
gets bumped off.

01:32.657 --> 01:34.877
There's been
a murder?

01:34.920 --> 01:37.967
MAN: Cue the entrance
of a world-weary detective,

01:38.010 --> 01:41.492
who comes in
and pokes his nose around.

01:41.536 --> 01:45.105
Talks to witnesses.
Takes a couple of wrong turns.

01:45.148 --> 01:48.760
And then gathers
all the suspects
in the drawing room

01:48.804 --> 01:51.285
and points the finger
at the least likely chump

01:51.328 --> 01:53.548
because of the way the guy,

01:53.591 --> 01:55.158
I don't know,

01:55.202 --> 01:56.986
ties his shoelaces.

01:57.029 --> 02:01.425
Now you've seen our play,
you're an accomplice
to murder.

02:01.469 --> 02:04.950
And so,
we ask you to remember

02:04.994 --> 02:07.823
that it is very much
in your interests

02:07.866 --> 02:12.480
not to tell a soul outside
of this theater who done it.

02:12.523 --> 02:14.090
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDS AND CHEERS]

02:14.134 --> 02:15.700
MAN: But what do I know?

02:15.744 --> 02:18.442
The Limeys,
they just lap it up.

02:18.486 --> 02:20.662
The play's a smash hit.[MAN CLEARS THROAT]

02:20.705 --> 02:23.099
Not to mention a cash cow.

02:23.143 --> 02:27.451
Right there is
the milkmaid in chief,
Petula Spencer.

02:36.504 --> 02:37.679
[RAT SQUEAKING]

02:39.855 --> 02:41.813
[MUSIC INTENSIFIES]

02:41.857 --> 02:45.687
[UPBEAT JAZZ MUSIC RESUMES][LAUGHTER AND CHATTER]

02:45.730 --> 02:51.040
This lavish affair
is a party to celebrate
the 100th performance.

02:51.083 --> 02:52.998
No wonder film producer
John Woolf

02:53.042 --> 02:56.393
wants to turn the play
into a major motion picture.

02:56.437 --> 03:00.441
Here he is now in the arms
of his slightly paranoid wife.

03:00.484 --> 03:03.487
I sense that death
is close at hand.

03:03.531 --> 03:05.794
It's probably
just a draft.

03:05.837 --> 03:07.796
MAN: This is where
I come in.

03:07.839 --> 03:09.928
Leo Kopernick's the name.

03:09.972 --> 03:12.670
Big-shot Hollywood director.

03:12.714 --> 03:14.890
Hired to make
the film adaptation

03:14.933 --> 03:18.459
marginally less boring
than the play.[CHUCKLES]

03:18.502 --> 03:23.159
Easier said than done
when the writer's
a giant pompous ass.

03:23.203 --> 03:25.292
Mervyn Cocker-Norris.

03:25.335 --> 03:27.294
I say,
you're rather tall.

03:27.337 --> 03:29.687
Am I? Haven't really
thought about it,
to be honest.

03:29.731 --> 03:31.776
Is that what
happened here?

03:31.820 --> 03:34.170
Sort of. I had
a bit of an accident
backstage.

03:34.214 --> 03:38.305
LEO: Sure, he's educated
and he knows
a lot of $10 words,

03:38.348 --> 03:41.090
but it's like
he's never seen
a film before,

03:41.133 --> 03:43.048
let alone try to write one.

03:43.092 --> 03:44.702
Oh, ma vattinne!

03:46.443 --> 03:47.618
Chi e chistu?

03:48.228 --> 03:49.707
No one important.

03:49.751 --> 03:52.232
Omm, femmina o bestia,
basta che respira!

03:52.275 --> 03:55.496
You know, at times
you do rather overdo
the temperamental Neapolitan.

03:56.148 --> 03:57.976
That's a nice jacket.

04:00.805 --> 04:04.635
Say, why don't you
scare me up a real drink,
will you, kid?

04:04.679 --> 04:09.510
Like a pint of rye
or bourbon or motor oil,
if you have to.

04:10.598 --> 04:12.556
Yeah. Hop to it,
now, huh?

04:12.600 --> 04:15.646
In England, that actually
counts as good service.

04:15.690 --> 04:17.692
I was stationed here
during the war

04:17.735 --> 04:20.738
and, if anything,
the locals are
more uptight now

04:20.782 --> 04:23.263
than when they had
the Luftwaffe overhead.

04:23.306 --> 04:24.438
Mervyn?

04:26.004 --> 04:27.005
Shouldn't you
be home?

04:27.049 --> 04:28.398
I thought we had
a deadline.

04:28.442 --> 04:29.921
I thought so too.

04:29.965 --> 04:32.402
But then
our esteemed director
tore up the screenplay

04:32.446 --> 04:34.883
and told me to start
all over again.

04:34.926 --> 04:37.886
He's of the opinion
that a modern audience
will walk out in protest

04:37.929 --> 04:41.759
if they're not served
at least one violent death
in the opening frames.

04:41.803 --> 04:44.762
Suffice to say,
we are no longer
on speaking terms.

04:45.502 --> 04:47.461
Merv! [SPITS]

04:47.504 --> 04:51.073
London's most
sensitive writer.
[CHUCKLES]

04:51.116 --> 04:52.640
How is
The Mousetrap,huh?

04:52.683 --> 04:54.250
Did they catch
the guy who did it?

04:54.294 --> 04:56.296
I will not stand here
and be insulted.

04:58.472 --> 05:00.038
Well, I guess
he's gonna go over there
and be insulted.

05:00.082 --> 05:01.866
Huh.

05:01.910 --> 05:05.696
LEO: [GROANS]
What passes for glamour
in these parts.

05:05.740 --> 05:08.873
Sheila Sim
and Dickie Attenborough.

05:08.917 --> 05:11.398
Kid likes the sound
of his own voice.

05:11.441 --> 05:13.574
Even money,
he makes a speech.

05:13.617 --> 05:15.706
I suppose
I ought to say
a few words.

05:15.750 --> 05:16.968
Not too many.

05:17.012 --> 05:19.449
And when have I ever?Our wedding, remember?

05:19.493 --> 05:20.798
We almost missed
the honeymoon.

05:20.842 --> 05:21.973
Yes.

05:22.017 --> 05:24.062
Darlings,
you're ever so kind.

05:24.106 --> 05:28.066
I'd like to ask
you all to raise
a metaphorical bat

05:28.110 --> 05:29.764
to the old pavilion.

05:29.807 --> 05:32.680
The Mousetrapis 100,
not out.

05:32.723 --> 05:34.246
Cheers!ALL: Cheers!

05:35.726 --> 05:38.294
LEO: I tell you
what else is 100 not out.

05:38.338 --> 05:40.209
Petula's mother.

05:40.252 --> 05:43.604
[CHUCKLES] The old kook's
just crazy about seafood.

05:43.647 --> 05:45.780
They just brought out
more langoustines.

05:45.823 --> 05:46.824
[CRAB LEG SNAPS]

05:48.130 --> 05:51.220
Excuse me,
I just need to
deal with that.

05:51.263 --> 05:52.352
Mother! Please,

05:52.395 --> 05:54.092
you've had
quite enough.Hi.

05:54.136 --> 05:56.791
Now, I'm not one
to tell tales
out of school,

05:56.834 --> 05:58.923
but the girls over here,

05:58.967 --> 06:01.404
they go wild
for an American accent

06:01.448 --> 06:03.667
and the promise
of a pair of nylons.

06:04.538 --> 06:06.017
But the husbands...

06:06.061 --> 06:08.368
Right. I think it's time
someone taught you
a lesson.

06:08.411 --> 06:10.108
LEO: ...they're not
so easily won over.

06:10.152 --> 06:13.024
It's only fair to warn you
that I learned to box
in the RAF.

06:13.068 --> 06:16.158
Yeah? Well, I learned
to fly a plane
in Gleason's Gym.

06:17.681 --> 06:19.596
[GUESTS EXCLAIM]

06:19.640 --> 06:21.424
[MUSIC ENDS]

06:21.468 --> 06:26.255
All of which explains,
in an admittedly
roundabout fashion,

06:26.298 --> 06:29.258
how I come to be
in the theater's
backstage area

06:29.301 --> 06:31.303
in need of
a change of clothes.

06:39.834 --> 06:41.226
[SOFT CREAK]

06:44.142 --> 06:45.143
Hello?

07:05.816 --> 07:06.817
[SCOFFS]

07:09.733 --> 07:11.256
[METAL SQUEAKS IN DISTANCE]

07:17.654 --> 07:18.612
Hello?

07:20.744 --> 07:21.702
[FLOORBOARD CREAKS]

07:22.529 --> 07:23.573
[GRUNTS]

07:23.617 --> 07:25.836
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

07:28.883 --> 07:30.014
[LEO GROANS]

07:47.771 --> 07:49.556
[GAGGING]

08:03.395 --> 08:04.658
[GASPING]

08:04.701 --> 08:06.268
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

08:17.322 --> 08:18.498
Aw, jeez.

08:19.194 --> 08:21.022
[MUSIC HALTS]

08:21.065 --> 08:23.807
I guess I should have
seen this coming.

08:23.851 --> 08:27.332
It's always the most
unlikable character
who gets bumped off.

08:27.376 --> 08:29.552
[THUMP][DRAMATIC NOTE PLAYS]

08:29.596 --> 08:31.380
It's a whodunit.

08:31.423 --> 08:34.209
You've seen one,
you've seen 'em all.

08:34.252 --> 08:36.211
[DRAMATIC NOTE PLAYS][THUNDER RUMBLING]

08:45.394 --> 08:49.050
[MYSTERIOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

08:53.576 --> 08:55.926
[THUNDER CONTINUES RUMBLING]

08:57.014 --> 08:58.755
[ENGINE REVS]

08:58.799 --> 08:59.887
[TIRES SQUEAL]

09:09.505 --> 09:10.985
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

09:11.028 --> 09:12.160
We're closed.

09:14.292 --> 09:16.164
[DOOR RATTLING]Clear off.

09:17.861 --> 09:19.559
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

09:19.602 --> 09:20.560
Honestly.

09:24.520 --> 09:27.567
Oh, I'm so sorry, sir.
Inspector, uh, Stoppard, sir.

09:27.610 --> 09:30.221
Sorry, I was under
strict instructions
not to let anyone in.

09:30.265 --> 09:31.745
Just open the door.

09:31.788 --> 09:33.485
Yes, sir. Of course.
Sorry, I didn't
recognize you, sir.

09:33.529 --> 09:35.792
I've actually,
uh, just been
transferred myself.

09:35.836 --> 09:38.578
Thought it was
Leeke and Priestley
on rotation tonight.

09:38.621 --> 09:40.405
[BUMPS]Careful, sir.

09:40.884 --> 09:42.059
In you come.

09:42.103 --> 09:43.234
[STOPPARD SIGHS]

09:49.110 --> 09:50.720
Constable.Stalker, sir.

09:52.026 --> 09:54.028
God, you're all
wet through, sir.

09:54.071 --> 09:56.030
Hope you don't
catch a cold
after that.

09:56.073 --> 09:57.161
Yep, after you, sir.

10:00.991 --> 10:04.038
Victim's name is
Leo Kopernick, sir.
The film director.

10:04.081 --> 10:06.344
Suspected Communist,
blacklisted
in Hollywood,

10:06.388 --> 10:09.913
so he came out here
to work on a picture
for John Woolf.

10:09.957 --> 10:11.915
You know John Woolf,
the film producer.

10:11.959 --> 10:14.352
He made
The African Queen
with Humphrey Bogart.

10:14.396 --> 10:15.876
[IMITATING ACTOR]
"Nature, Mr. Allnut,

10:15.919 --> 10:19.053
"is what we are
put in this world
to rise above."

10:19.096 --> 10:21.055
That didn't sound
anything like Bogart.

10:21.098 --> 10:23.623
No, that was
Katharine Hepburn, sir.
She's in it too.

10:23.666 --> 10:25.059
Wonderful actress.

10:25.102 --> 10:27.235
I go to the pictures
quite a lot, actually.

10:27.278 --> 10:28.671
It's the escape,
I suppose.

10:28.715 --> 10:29.933
The romance of
the silver screen.

10:29.977 --> 10:30.978
Yes, thank you, Constable.

10:31.021 --> 10:32.153
Yes, sir.

10:33.633 --> 10:35.199
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

10:37.332 --> 10:38.420
[CHATTER QUIETS]

10:50.171 --> 10:51.563
[WOMAN COUGHS]

10:55.655 --> 10:58.527
Eh, signs of a struggle.

10:58.570 --> 11:00.268
STALKER: Actually, sir,
I believe that happened

11:00.311 --> 11:01.661
when Mrs. Boyle
was killed.

11:01.704 --> 11:03.097
Mrs. Boyle? Who's...

11:03.140 --> 11:05.229
Yes, sir. Um...

11:05.273 --> 11:06.448
She's that woman
in the front row there.

11:09.494 --> 11:11.235
Well, she seems
to have bounced back.

11:12.149 --> 11:13.716
Oh. [CHUCKLES]

11:13.760 --> 11:16.588
Sorry, sir. No,
she was killed in the play.
Also strangled.

11:16.632 --> 11:18.547
Not that I've seen it,
although I would like to.

11:18.590 --> 11:21.811
It's an Agatha Christie,
and I do like
a good murder.

11:21.855 --> 11:23.813
Yes, thank you, Constable.

11:23.857 --> 11:24.814
Yes, sir.

11:27.643 --> 11:29.645
[EERIE MUSIC PLAYING]

11:34.345 --> 11:36.608
A ski did that, sir.

11:36.652 --> 11:38.567
They use it
in the play,
apparently.

11:38.610 --> 11:40.830
As I said,
I haven't seen it.

11:40.874 --> 11:44.529
And then the large dent
in the cranium
is a sewing machine.

11:44.573 --> 11:46.793
Seems he was killed
in the costume store
initially,

11:46.836 --> 11:48.620
and then he was
deposited here.

11:50.579 --> 11:52.407
Staged,
so to speak.
[CHUCKLES]

11:54.757 --> 11:55.715
Sorry, sir.

12:04.071 --> 12:06.464
Yeah, that's the ski
that he took
in the face, sir.

12:06.508 --> 12:09.032
And, uh, I'm afraid
it was downhill
from there.

12:10.338 --> 12:12.253
Oh. Sorry, sir.

12:12.296 --> 12:13.907
That one just came out
on its own. [CHUCKLES]

12:16.605 --> 12:17.649
[STALKER CLEARS THROAT]

12:22.002 --> 12:23.046
Seems he came
down here

12:23.090 --> 12:24.047
for a change
of clothes.

12:26.441 --> 12:27.442
Why?

12:33.491 --> 12:36.886
It was a party to celebrate
the 100th performance, sir.

12:36.930 --> 12:38.192
The other nought
must have...

12:38.235 --> 12:41.238
When the victim
upset the sponge.

12:41.282 --> 12:45.808
Um, and he then proceeded
to sit in the assortment
of crustaceans.

12:45.852 --> 12:48.202
[GRUNTS][GUESTS EXCLAIM]

12:52.206 --> 12:56.079
I'm told he was
intoxicated, sir,
as a newt. [CHUCKLES]

12:56.123 --> 12:58.821
This was actually
a lot more fun than
I thought it would be.

13:00.214 --> 13:01.693
[SOMBER MUSIC PLAYS]

13:05.436 --> 13:08.222
Then he left. No one
saw him again until
the body was discovered.

13:08.265 --> 13:09.353
That's correct, sir.

13:10.964 --> 13:13.314
[SIGHS] Perhaps they were
all in on it together, sir?

13:17.361 --> 13:18.493
Hmm.

13:23.411 --> 13:24.412
[SOFT CRUNCH]

13:26.893 --> 13:27.894
[CAMERA FLASHBULB POPS]

13:30.461 --> 13:33.334
Looks like the killer
tried to pull out
the victim's tongue.

13:33.377 --> 13:35.945
Why would anyone
do a thing like that?

13:35.989 --> 13:38.600
Excuse me,
Chief Inspector.

13:38.643 --> 13:39.819
It's just
"Inspector."

13:39.862 --> 13:41.995
Yes. Of course.
Inspector.

13:42.038 --> 13:43.823
I hate to interrupt,
I do.

13:43.866 --> 13:45.172
There really is
nothing worse...

13:45.215 --> 13:47.739
Petula Spencer, sir.
Prominent theater
impresario.

13:47.783 --> 13:49.437
Yes, thank you,
Constable.

13:49.480 --> 13:53.049
Tell me, how much longer
do you intend to keep us
all hostage here?

13:53.093 --> 13:54.355
Or is that
the idea?

13:54.398 --> 13:56.966
"Let the galled
jade wince."

13:57.010 --> 13:58.663
Gather all
the suspects
under one roof

13:58.707 --> 14:01.405
and then interrogate
each of us in turn until
the mystery is solved?

14:01.449 --> 14:03.538
Mervyn Cocker-Norris,
overrated playwright.

14:03.581 --> 14:05.105
Celebrated
playwright.

14:06.062 --> 14:07.368
Oh, I'm so sorry, sir.

14:07.411 --> 14:09.109
I can't read
me own handwriting.

14:09.152 --> 14:11.328
Not that
we are suspects,
necessarily.

14:13.983 --> 14:14.941
Are we suspects?

14:16.768 --> 14:18.727
It was just
a reference to
Agatha Christie

14:18.770 --> 14:20.729
and her penchant
for denouement,

14:20.772 --> 14:23.123
in which the detective
gathers the susp...

14:24.080 --> 14:26.343
I dare say,
that's not...

14:26.387 --> 14:28.476
Please continue.Yes, thank you, Mervyn.

14:28.519 --> 14:30.391
Inspector,
I want you to know

14:30.434 --> 14:33.307
that I have nothing
but the utmost respect

14:33.350 --> 14:35.352
for the Metropolitan Police.

14:35.396 --> 14:37.659
But, well, do you think
you might be finished

14:37.702 --> 14:39.226
in time for curtain up
tomorrow night?

14:39.269 --> 14:40.401
Oh, for goodness' sake.

14:40.444 --> 14:42.185
John Woolf,
esteemed
film producer.

14:42.229 --> 14:43.578
Yes, thank you,
Constable.

14:43.621 --> 14:45.536
This is
a murder
investigation.

14:45.580 --> 14:49.105
Surely that
takes precedence,
sold out or not.

14:49.149 --> 14:51.238
Yes, it's all going
to plan for you,
isn't it, Woolfie?

14:51.281 --> 14:52.674
You want the run to end.

14:52.717 --> 14:55.111
WOOLF: [SCOFFS]
I want nothing
of the sort.

14:55.155 --> 14:56.808
It's the decent thing
to do, that's all.

14:56.852 --> 14:59.376
Close the theater
out of respect for Leo.

14:59.420 --> 15:00.769
Such a tragic loss.

15:00.812 --> 15:06.340
Inspector,
I implore you
not to overreact.

15:06.383 --> 15:09.256
I would hate
to have to go
over your head and

15:09.299 --> 15:11.911
talk directly
to your superiors.

15:11.954 --> 15:13.738
Oh, we wouldn't
want that, now,
would we, madam?

15:13.782 --> 15:15.784
But I'm afraid that
under the circumstances,

15:15.827 --> 15:17.829
as a precaution...Precaution?

15:18.656 --> 15:20.136
He's already dead.

15:20.180 --> 15:21.833
STOPPARD: He is, madam.

15:21.877 --> 15:24.227
But until we have an idea
as to a likely motive,

15:24.271 --> 15:26.447
who's to say
this is the end
of it?

15:26.490 --> 15:28.449
What is that
supposed to mean?

15:28.492 --> 15:31.147
We are no longer
merely suspects.

15:31.191 --> 15:33.976
We are also
potential victims.

15:35.717 --> 15:36.892
[CAMERA FLASHBULB POPS]Oh.

15:37.414 --> 15:38.981
Mmm.

15:39.025 --> 15:41.810
Oh, God,
I wasn't in that, was I?
I must look dreadful.

15:43.072 --> 15:45.292
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

15:49.774 --> 15:51.167
[TIRES SQUEAL][ENGINE REVS]

15:56.956 --> 15:58.609
[INDISTINCT CONVERSATIONS]

16:07.140 --> 16:08.184
Excuse me, sir.

16:16.845 --> 16:17.889
[BLOWS NOSE]

16:17.933 --> 16:19.239
MAN: Stoppard!

16:19.282 --> 16:21.241
My office.

16:21.284 --> 16:23.417
[KNOCK ON DOOR]STOPPARD: Hello, sir.

16:23.460 --> 16:24.766
What in God's name
possessed you

16:24.809 --> 16:26.550
to close down
the Ambassadors?

16:26.594 --> 16:28.204
Uh, protocol, sir.
It's a crime scene.

16:28.248 --> 16:31.512
No, it's a public relations
disaster, is what it is.

16:31.555 --> 16:32.687
Public what, sir?

16:32.730 --> 16:34.036
Stalker!Sir.

16:34.080 --> 16:35.995
Not to put too
fine a point on...

16:36.038 --> 16:37.344
Yes, please.Here.

16:37.387 --> 16:38.998
Not to put
too fine a point
on it, Inspector,

16:39.041 --> 16:42.566
but your latest blunder
is front page news.

16:42.610 --> 16:43.915
Fleet Street
is all over this,

16:43.959 --> 16:45.830
like hot jam
on a Devonshire scone.

16:45.874 --> 16:49.443
You are slap-bang
in the crosshairs.

16:49.486 --> 16:51.053
Now, we need to do
everything we can

16:51.097 --> 16:53.882
to make sure the bullet
doesn't miss you and hit me.

16:53.925 --> 16:55.884
Yeah, of course, sir. Yes.Good.

16:55.927 --> 16:57.842
Then you'll inform
the theater at once.

16:57.886 --> 16:59.540
Well, I thought
as a precaution, I...

16:59.583 --> 17:01.063
The Home Secretary

17:01.107 --> 17:03.892
is a close, personal friend
of Agatha Christie.

17:03.935 --> 17:06.155
His brother-in-law
is Rex Harrison.

17:06.199 --> 17:07.243
Wonderful actor.

17:07.287 --> 17:09.202
Yes, thank you, Constable.Sir.

17:09.245 --> 17:11.552
It's actually worked
in our favor to have the press
distracted like this.

17:11.595 --> 17:15.034
It means we can keep a lid on
the Rillington Place murders.

17:15.077 --> 17:18.080
Rillington Place murders.
Yes. What's that?

17:18.124 --> 17:19.864
[SIGHS] Blimey.

17:19.908 --> 17:21.736
Haven't you heard?

17:21.779 --> 17:23.868
We have
a serial killer
on the loose.

17:23.912 --> 17:26.175
You didn't think
all of this was for you,
now, did you?

17:28.047 --> 17:29.526
No, of course...No.

17:29.570 --> 17:31.876
[BOTH CHUCKLE]Of course not.

17:31.920 --> 17:35.445
Well, have all the resources
been allocated
to this other investigation?

17:35.489 --> 17:38.057
No, not all of them, no.

17:38.100 --> 17:41.103
I understand you,
uh, met WPC Stalker
last night?

17:41.147 --> 17:42.409
I did, yes.

17:42.452 --> 17:44.019
Constable.Inspector.

17:44.063 --> 17:48.154
A very capable
officer.

17:48.197 --> 17:50.634
Or at least she will be
once she gets
the proper instruction.

17:51.679 --> 17:53.159
Sorry, sir,
I'm not sure I, uh...

17:53.202 --> 17:54.508
You don't mean
you want me to...

17:54.551 --> 17:57.380
Yes, I do. I'd like you
to show her the ropes.

17:57.424 --> 18:01.123
I'm hoping some of her
enthusiasm for police work
might rub off on you.

18:01.167 --> 18:03.256
But the, uh, bullet, sir.
Is that why...

18:03.299 --> 18:05.910
This is not
a debate, Stoppard.

18:05.954 --> 18:08.739
I have a reputation
as a modernizer.

18:08.783 --> 18:10.785
I have to be seen
to keep it up.

18:10.828 --> 18:13.614
I have said in public

18:13.657 --> 18:16.791
that I think
women are the future
of the force.

18:16.834 --> 18:19.837
Absolutely, sir,
I agree.

18:19.881 --> 18:20.925
[CHUCKLING]
But we're not looking

18:20.969 --> 18:22.318
for stolen sweets...Sweets.

18:22.362 --> 18:24.103
...or a lost
bleeding bicycle.

18:24.146 --> 18:26.801
This is
a murder investigation,
and she is inexperienced.

18:26.844 --> 18:30.805
They were
inexperienced
in the war.

18:30.848 --> 18:32.937
Ask Jerry
how that turned out.

18:32.981 --> 18:34.374
Yes, sir. But, uh...

18:34.417 --> 18:35.505
That...Huh?

18:35.549 --> 18:38.726
...will be all.Thank you.

18:39.596 --> 18:40.771
Commissioner.Inspector.

18:41.946 --> 18:43.905
Constable.Inspector.

18:45.167 --> 18:47.169
Commissioner.Constable.

18:47.213 --> 18:49.432
Um, sorry again
about last night, sir.

18:49.476 --> 18:50.868
With the rain
and everything...

18:50.912 --> 18:52.261
Water under
the bridge, Constable.
No harm done.

18:52.305 --> 18:53.349
[SNEEZES]

18:53.393 --> 18:55.482
[PLAYFUL JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

18:55.525 --> 18:57.484
[SNIFFLES,
GROANS]

18:59.050 --> 19:00.835
[SNEEZES]You all right?

19:00.878 --> 19:05.100
Yeah. Do we have
an address
for the victim?

19:05.144 --> 19:09.148
Yep. It is
"Laurel Canyon,
Hollywood, USA."

19:10.845 --> 19:13.195
Where was he staying
in England, Constable?

19:14.675 --> 19:16.242
Oh. Um...

19:16.285 --> 19:18.026
[TUTS] Right.

19:18.069 --> 19:20.463
[PLAYFUL JAZZ MUSIC CONTINUES]

19:35.957 --> 19:37.219
[ELEVATOR BELL DINGS]

19:38.873 --> 19:41.267
If I am honest,
MonsieurKopernick,

19:41.310 --> 19:43.138
he was not
a very good guest.

19:43.182 --> 19:44.357
In arrears,
was he?

19:44.400 --> 19:47.882
La, non,
but he did not pay
for his room.

19:47.925 --> 19:49.318
MonsieurWoolf did.

19:49.362 --> 19:50.363
STALKER: Hmm.

19:51.929 --> 19:53.757
What part of France
are you from, sir?

19:54.584 --> 19:55.672
Belgium.

19:56.195 --> 19:57.196
Ah, right.

20:01.461 --> 20:03.811
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

20:03.854 --> 20:05.943
[DOOR CLOSES]STOPPARD: Oh, my, my.

20:08.032 --> 20:10.383
What a bloody pigsty.

20:10.426 --> 20:13.168
They don't clean
the rooms
at the Savoy?

20:13.212 --> 20:15.170
Helas,not this one.

20:15.953 --> 20:17.041
Hmm.

20:17.085 --> 20:19.435
The maids,
they refuse.

20:19.479 --> 20:23.091
We offer them more money,
but still they say non.

20:24.048 --> 20:25.224
There was

20:26.181 --> 20:28.749
an incident.

20:28.792 --> 20:32.448
Always avec
MonsieurKopernick,
there was an incident.

20:38.367 --> 20:39.325
Hmm.

20:51.511 --> 20:52.468
Ooh.

20:53.426 --> 20:54.949
STOPPARD:
Thank you,
Constable.

20:54.992 --> 20:57.168
Oh. Sorry, sir.

20:57.212 --> 20:59.475
Did one of these incidents
ever turn violent?

21:00.171 --> 21:02.435
Oui. Une fois.

21:02.478 --> 21:04.306
[ROUSING MUSIC PLAYS]

21:04.350 --> 21:06.047
MERVYN: How dare you
call me a bad writer!

21:06.090 --> 21:07.701
LEO: I didn't say that.
I said it's bad writing.

21:07.744 --> 21:10.094
MERVYN: I did the best
I could within the confines
of the genre,

21:10.138 --> 21:12.183
and Woolf loved it!

21:12.227 --> 21:14.229
LEO: Woolf wouldn't know
a good script if it came up
and bit him on the ass.

21:14.273 --> 21:16.840
It's horseshit!No, it isn't!
Not all of it!

21:16.884 --> 21:18.364
All right, what I read
is horseshit!

21:18.407 --> 21:21.018
MERVYN: [GASPS]
You mean you didn't
even finish it?

21:21.062 --> 21:22.455
I read enough, pal,

21:22.498 --> 21:23.934
to know that
nobody gets killed
in the first 10 pages!

21:23.978 --> 21:26.154
You charlatan!
Give it back!

21:26.197 --> 21:27.634
Listen. Listen to me. Listen!Give...

21:27.677 --> 21:29.549
We need to go
in a completely
different direction!

21:29.592 --> 21:30.724
[STRAINING]

21:30.767 --> 21:32.073
[LEO GRUNTS][YELPS]

21:32.116 --> 21:33.553
[LAMP SHATTERS]

21:35.250 --> 21:36.599
[PANTING]

21:36.643 --> 21:40.299
I'll kill you for this,
Kopernick, you bastard!

21:43.867 --> 21:46.914
That's that then, sir.
It's as good
as a confession.

21:46.957 --> 21:49.438
Let's not jump
to conclusions,
Constable.

21:49.830 --> 21:51.266
No, sir.

21:51.310 --> 21:53.747
The least we can do is
talk to this other party.

21:53.790 --> 21:55.531
Yes, sir.
Cocker-Norris, sir.

21:58.229 --> 21:59.753
STOPPARD: Tell me,
do you write
everything down

21:59.796 --> 22:01.929
in that little notebook?

22:01.972 --> 22:04.061
Only if it's
important, sir.

22:04.105 --> 22:05.672
How do you know
if it's important?

22:07.064 --> 22:08.979
Well,

22:09.023 --> 22:12.853
uh, I'll just sort of
put everything in
as we go,

22:12.896 --> 22:15.203
and then down the line
when we know
what's important,

22:15.246 --> 22:17.205
we'll know
that it's already
in the notebook.

22:20.208 --> 22:21.601
So you do write
everything down.

22:21.644 --> 22:22.732
Yeah, everything.

22:23.472 --> 22:24.734
That's what I thought.

22:26.606 --> 22:27.911
[ENGINE STARTS]

22:29.870 --> 22:32.655
[OPERATIC SONG PLAYING]

22:37.399 --> 22:38.661
MERVYN:
Make yourself
comfortable.

22:38.705 --> 22:40.881
You're just in time
for elevenses.

23:02.250 --> 23:03.425
[GRUNTS]Oh.

23:04.948 --> 23:07.647
[SONG CONTINUES PLAYING]

23:13.696 --> 23:14.697
Oh!

23:15.785 --> 23:16.743
[DOOR OPENS]

23:17.831 --> 23:18.788
[DOOR CLOSES]

23:20.224 --> 23:21.704
[OPERA STOPS]

23:21.748 --> 23:24.446
You must excuse
the desordre,

23:24.490 --> 23:26.622
it's research for
the film adaptation.

23:26.666 --> 23:29.930
Police statements,
court reports,
newspaper cuttings.

23:29.973 --> 23:32.411
The Mousetrapis
actually based on
a real-life case.

23:33.063 --> 23:34.630
Nettle tea?

23:34.674 --> 23:37.503
I appreciate you've
not yet had time
to come to terms

23:37.546 --> 23:39.026
with the death of
Mr. Kopernick, but...

23:39.069 --> 23:40.941
Is it true
his tongue was
pulled out?

23:40.984 --> 23:42.769
[CHUCKLING]
I'm afraid I can't
divulge details

23:42.812 --> 23:43.857
of an ongoing
investigation.

23:43.900 --> 23:45.206
It was disgusting.

23:45.249 --> 23:47.948
[DOOR OPENS] Amore, non pozzo
fatica cosi!

23:47.991 --> 23:49.036
What?

23:50.037 --> 23:51.821
E na cos' 'e pazz!

23:51.865 --> 23:53.432
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS]

23:58.132 --> 23:59.481
[CHUCKLES LIGHTLY]

23:59.525 --> 24:03.659
That's Gio.
Nephew of mine.
Very hotheaded.

24:03.703 --> 24:05.444
I wonder if it isn't
all the fumes.

24:05.487 --> 24:06.923
You know,
from the chemicals.

24:06.967 --> 24:09.230
He's an amateur taxidermist.

24:09.273 --> 24:12.668
He has a fascination
with the macabre.

24:12.712 --> 24:14.453
I call it his
Stymphalian Bird series.

24:14.975 --> 24:16.716
STOPPARD: Hmm.

24:16.759 --> 24:19.719
MERVYN: Macabre in a strictly
"ornithological" sense,
that is.

24:22.896 --> 24:24.593
You wanted to ask me
about Leo?

24:24.637 --> 24:27.074
STOPPARD: We heard
there was an argument
at the Savoy,

24:27.117 --> 24:28.641
and I noticed you had
the other half of this.

24:34.777 --> 24:37.954
Inspector,
that was a contretemps,
nothing more.

24:37.998 --> 24:40.522
[SOFTLY] Read that part.
Yeah.

24:40.566 --> 24:43.699
"I'll kill you for this,
Kopernick, you bastard."

24:47.094 --> 24:48.356
Well, obviously, I...

24:48.399 --> 24:50.314
Taken out of context, I...

24:50.358 --> 24:54.971
Those words were spoken
in anger and under
extreme provocation.

24:55.015 --> 24:57.278
We had creative differences,
that's all.

24:58.061 --> 24:59.585
Hmm.

24:59.628 --> 25:01.238
How did you
like The Mousetrap?

25:02.065 --> 25:03.763
Oh, yeah, the play?Mmm.

25:03.806 --> 25:05.678
Yeah, I, uh...
I didn't see it yet.

25:05.721 --> 25:06.766
Well, if you'd like,

25:06.809 --> 25:08.028
I can precis this...No, no, no.

25:08.071 --> 25:10.596
I got the basics.
It's a whodunit, right?

25:10.639 --> 25:14.513
So, you got
a dead body,
a detective,

25:14.556 --> 25:17.428
and then all the suspects
rather conveniently

25:17.472 --> 25:19.561
end up in a remote
country house together.

25:20.170 --> 25:21.868
In a nutshell.

25:21.911 --> 25:24.653
Our task will be to
present this improbable
series of events

25:24.697 --> 25:26.612
to an audience of
moderate intelligence

25:26.655 --> 25:29.136
in a manner
that does not cause
too much offense.

25:29.179 --> 25:30.616
Easy.

25:30.659 --> 25:31.834
Flashbacks.

25:32.269 --> 25:33.749
No.

25:34.402 --> 25:35.621
No what?

25:35.664 --> 25:37.448
No flashbacks.

25:37.492 --> 25:39.363
They are crass, lazy,
and they interrupt

25:39.407 --> 25:41.061
the flow of the story.

25:41.104 --> 25:44.325
In my opinion,
they are the last refuge
of a moribund imagination.

25:44.847 --> 25:45.979
Whatever next?

25:46.022 --> 25:48.372
A caption that says,
"Three weeks later"?

25:48.416 --> 25:50.113
[DRAMATIC NOTE PLAYS]

25:50.810 --> 25:51.854
[KNOCKING ON DOOR]

25:51.898 --> 25:54.465
Merv. Merv,
will you come on?

25:54.509 --> 25:55.858
This is crazy.
Will you open the door?

25:55.902 --> 25:57.556
I'm not coming out
until Woolf gets here.

25:57.599 --> 25:58.557
[DOOR BUZZES]

26:00.123 --> 26:01.385
What is it this time?

26:01.429 --> 26:02.909
I'll tell you
what it is.

26:02.952 --> 26:04.475
I pitched
a new ending,

26:04.519 --> 26:07.130
Cockamamie-Novice over here
locks himself in the bathroom.

26:07.174 --> 26:08.915
Is this instead
of the car chase?

26:08.958 --> 26:10.394
As well as.

26:10.438 --> 26:14.181
I think he thinks
"denouement" is French
for "shootout."

26:14.224 --> 26:15.748
Will you at least
hear me out first,

26:15.791 --> 26:18.228
and then tell me
you don't like it?

26:18.272 --> 26:22.015
Come on,
I storyboarded it for you.
Come on, have a seat.

26:22.058 --> 26:25.235
MERVYN: Why can't we just
have the detective gather
everyone in the drawing room

26:25.279 --> 26:27.629
and then
reveal to them
who did it?

26:27.673 --> 26:30.719
Why? 'Cause it's old,
it's tired.

26:30.763 --> 26:32.460
It's been done
a thousand times.

26:32.503 --> 26:35.376
So then who explains
to the audience
what on Earth's going on?

26:35.419 --> 26:36.507
No one.

26:36.551 --> 26:38.509
I don't know.
The killer.

26:38.553 --> 26:40.076
Now you see
what I have to
put up with?

26:40.120 --> 26:42.035
Will you please
have a seat?

26:42.078 --> 26:44.777
So, a remote
country house.

26:44.820 --> 26:48.171
We got all the, uh,
suspects gathered in
the drawing room, right?

26:48.215 --> 26:50.652
So far, soporific.

26:50.696 --> 26:52.915
Suddenly,
the lights go out.

26:52.959 --> 26:54.438
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

26:54.482 --> 26:58.051
Our hero grips
his Colt Special,
edges into the hall.

26:59.792 --> 27:02.011
The killer's got a hostage,
can't get a clear shot.

27:03.056 --> 27:04.492
Suddenly, kaboom!

27:04.535 --> 27:06.146
The place goes up
in flames.

27:06.189 --> 27:07.277
[CARD SHUFFLES]

27:07.321 --> 27:08.409
Blam! Blam!

27:08.452 --> 27:10.106
Our hero
plugs the killer.

27:10.150 --> 27:11.412
One in the gut!
[GRUNTS]

27:11.455 --> 27:13.196
One in the knee!
[GROANS]

27:13.240 --> 27:14.371
Then, all of a sudden...

27:14.415 --> 27:15.721
[MIMICS GUN CLICKING]

27:16.547 --> 27:18.288
His goddamned gun jams.

27:18.332 --> 27:19.507
He's a sittin' duck.

27:21.291 --> 27:22.336
Sorry, not that one.

27:22.379 --> 27:23.424
[CARDS SHUFFLING]

27:23.467 --> 27:24.512
I'm sorry about this.

27:25.469 --> 27:26.514
He's a sittin' duck.

27:26.557 --> 27:27.776
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

27:27.820 --> 27:30.518
Our killer,
dying but not dead,

27:31.562 --> 27:32.651
takes aim.

27:33.347 --> 27:35.218
Boom! He fires.

27:35.262 --> 27:36.742
Out of nowhere,

27:36.785 --> 27:39.570
our hero cop's partner
dives in slow motion!

27:39.614 --> 27:40.615
Takes a bullet!

27:40.963 --> 27:42.661
[GRUNTS]

27:42.704 --> 27:48.579
Our hero cradles his partner
like a father would his child.

27:48.623 --> 27:51.321
His face
a gumbo of emotions.

27:52.888 --> 27:55.412
We hold on the inferno,

27:57.023 --> 27:59.634
and we pan left,
to a dead butler.

28:00.591 --> 28:01.897
[SOFT MUSIC PLAYING]

28:01.941 --> 28:03.856
Hank Williams plays us out.

28:05.074 --> 28:06.032
I Saw The Light.

28:14.170 --> 28:16.738
You hate it.No, no,
I don't hate it.

28:16.782 --> 28:18.958
But you don't love it.Of course he doesn't!

28:19.001 --> 28:20.307
It's preposterous

28:20.350 --> 28:22.613
and totally out of keeping
with the rest of the film.

28:22.657 --> 28:24.006
Oh, who cares?

28:24.050 --> 28:25.747
The audience
only ever remembers
the last 20 minutes.

28:25.791 --> 28:27.227
Oh, poppycock.

28:27.270 --> 28:28.924
Uh, Hitchcock,
actually.

28:28.968 --> 28:30.404
How does
he get the gun?

28:30.883 --> 28:31.927
He's a cop!

28:31.971 --> 28:34.321
Uh, police are
not armed in England.

28:34.364 --> 28:36.410
What?
How do they kill
the bad guys?

28:36.453 --> 28:37.759
They don't.

28:37.803 --> 28:40.762
They ask them to stop
in the name of the law.

28:40.806 --> 28:42.285
[CAR HORN HONKING]Huh.

28:42.329 --> 28:43.678
Well, he fought
in the war,

28:43.722 --> 28:46.159
so he kept
his service revolver.

28:46.202 --> 28:48.944
God damn it,
we're gonna have to
pick this up another time.

28:50.859 --> 28:53.340
Say, uh, Merv.

28:53.383 --> 28:56.256
You wouldn't want to
lend me this pad,
would you?

28:56.299 --> 28:57.997
Just for the night.

28:58.040 --> 29:01.174
Only I got this dame
parked outside
I wanna impress.

29:01.217 --> 29:03.219
As in,
she actually
is a dame.

29:04.351 --> 29:06.919
And, well, you know.
[CHUCKLES]

29:06.962 --> 29:09.660
My place ain't exactly
the Savoy.

29:09.704 --> 29:12.228
I thought his place
exactly was the Savoy.

29:12.272 --> 29:15.188
No, he didn't take up
residence there
till a month later.

29:15.231 --> 29:18.365
And the production company
footed the bill when he did.

29:18.408 --> 29:20.193
How he finagled that,
I'll never know.

29:20.236 --> 29:21.629
[SLURPS]

29:21.672 --> 29:24.066
Either I need a new agent,
or he had dirt on Woolf.

29:24.501 --> 29:25.589
Hmm.

29:28.549 --> 29:29.724
[SWALLOWS]

29:29.768 --> 29:31.595
Did you ever meet
these women?

29:31.639 --> 29:33.336
[CLEARS THROAT]Who were they?

29:33.380 --> 29:35.469
Oh, girls he met
during the war

29:35.512 --> 29:37.558
who had low standards
and even lower self-esteem.

29:37.601 --> 29:38.994
I never had the pleasure.

29:41.431 --> 29:42.432
Oh, wait.

29:43.651 --> 29:44.739
Tell a lie.

29:44.783 --> 29:47.220
[PLAYFUL JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

29:47.263 --> 29:48.787
LEO: Merv! Come on.

29:48.830 --> 29:50.527
When I said we should
tear up the script,

29:50.571 --> 29:51.790
I didn't mean literally!

29:55.924 --> 29:57.230
Hello, Leo.

29:57.273 --> 29:58.405
What is that
doing here?

29:58.448 --> 29:59.623
[GASPS]

29:59.667 --> 30:01.234
He was
Kopernick's son!

30:01.277 --> 30:02.496
Peas in a pod.

30:03.105 --> 30:04.541
And the mother?

30:04.585 --> 30:07.718
I didn't get a good look.
A plain girl, rather homely.

30:08.502 --> 30:10.112
Dark hair, glasses,

30:10.156 --> 30:11.157
thick lenses.

30:12.462 --> 30:14.029
So there we have it, sir.
Cherchez la femme.

30:14.073 --> 30:15.378
STOPPARD: What?

30:15.422 --> 30:16.815
It's Belgian, sir.
It means,
"Look for the woman."

30:16.858 --> 30:19.295
I know what it means,
Constable. What woman?

30:19.339 --> 30:21.776
The mother
of Kopernick's
illegitimate son.

30:21.820 --> 30:23.647
Cocker-Norris
couldn't remember
her name,

30:23.691 --> 30:25.301
but I bet it's in
that little black book.

30:25.345 --> 30:27.477
You know,
the one that you found
in the hotel room, sir.

30:27.521 --> 30:29.175
If we find her,
we have our answer.

30:29.218 --> 30:31.046
We need to get
a police sketch artist
down here at once

30:31.090 --> 30:32.439
before he forgets
anything.

30:32.961 --> 30:35.007
[SIGHS]

30:35.050 --> 30:37.923
Mmm. I'm doing it again,
aren't I, sir?

30:37.966 --> 30:39.838
Jumping to conclusions.Conclusions, yeah.

30:39.881 --> 30:40.926
Little bit.

30:40.969 --> 30:41.927
Sorry.

30:42.536 --> 30:43.537
Constable.

30:45.887 --> 30:47.889
I have a very important
mission for you.

30:47.933 --> 30:49.064
Mmm-hmm.

30:49.108 --> 30:51.458
I need you to find
a telephone box.

30:51.501 --> 30:52.894
Call the station.

30:52.938 --> 30:55.679
Get an address
for John Woolf,
the film producer.

30:55.723 --> 30:57.072
And I'll wait
for you here.

30:57.116 --> 30:59.509
Uh, "Romulus Films, Soho,"
sir. I wrote it down.

31:00.597 --> 31:01.990
You did?Mmm-hmm.

31:04.253 --> 31:05.646
[SMACKS LIPS] Right.

31:06.473 --> 31:08.040
Well done.Thank you.

31:09.084 --> 31:10.303
[ENGINE STARTS]Shall we?

31:10.346 --> 31:12.305
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

31:18.920 --> 31:20.574
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

31:20.617 --> 31:22.054
[BELL RINGS]

31:22.097 --> 31:23.490
Uh, telegram
came for you.

31:26.145 --> 31:27.711
[GROANS]Bad news?

31:27.755 --> 31:29.148
It's the studio.

31:29.191 --> 31:30.845
Grace Kelly's doing
a Hitchcock picture
for Warner,

31:30.889 --> 31:32.673
so it's Dial M for
Maybe Next Time.

31:32.716 --> 31:34.327
Grace Kelly?Yes.

31:34.370 --> 31:35.589
For the part
you promised Sheila?

31:35.632 --> 31:37.852
Yes, that's right.

31:37.896 --> 31:40.246
Which is why
this is such
good news.

31:40.289 --> 31:41.247
[CLEARS THROAT]

31:42.596 --> 31:43.989
Ann?

31:44.032 --> 31:45.599
Darling,
what's the matter?

31:45.642 --> 31:47.514
You do know a promise
is only a promise
if you keep it.

31:47.557 --> 31:48.863
What do you mean?

31:48.907 --> 31:49.995
I mean you promised me
a night out months ago.

31:50.038 --> 31:51.300
I have been
so busy lately.

31:51.344 --> 31:52.736
Yes, I know.
I am your assistant.

31:52.780 --> 31:54.347
I promise,
as soon as I have
a moment to spare...

31:54.390 --> 31:55.870
Well, you're free
on Wednesday.

31:55.914 --> 31:57.567
Am I?
Are you sure?Mmm. Yes.

31:57.611 --> 31:59.265
I thought I was...No.

31:59.308 --> 32:00.875
No, well,
you should know.

32:00.919 --> 32:02.746
You are my assistant,
after all.

32:02.790 --> 32:04.487
Well, that's settled, then.
It's a date.

32:04.531 --> 32:05.967
I promise
I will take you out.

32:06.011 --> 32:07.490
I'm afraid, Mr. Woolf,
you really must be
going now,

32:07.534 --> 32:08.665
otherwise
you'll be late.

32:08.709 --> 32:10.319
Ah, right.
Thank you.Mmm.

32:11.494 --> 32:12.713
No, I'm serious.

32:12.756 --> 32:13.757
You do actually
need to get back
to Romulus.

32:13.801 --> 32:15.020
Oh. Right.
Okay. Yes.Yes.

32:23.071 --> 32:24.159
[EXHALES DEEPLY]

32:24.203 --> 32:27.119
This is exciting,
isn't it, sir?

32:27.162 --> 32:28.555
I'd say this is
the type of thing

32:28.598 --> 32:30.470
that made you want to
become a police officer,
was it?

32:33.125 --> 32:37.433
[SMACKS LIPS]
Me? I just sort of
fell into it, really.

32:38.608 --> 32:40.045
They needed people
after the war,

32:40.088 --> 32:41.829
and I needed
the money, so...

32:41.872 --> 32:43.352
[SIGHS]

32:43.396 --> 32:45.876
No, it's true.
The hours
can be unsociable,

32:45.920 --> 32:48.314
but I can't type
or stand the sight
of blood,

32:48.357 --> 32:50.925
so that ruled out
secretary for me.

32:50.969 --> 32:51.970
Mmm.

32:57.192 --> 32:58.889
You don't mind
if I pick your brains,
do you, sir?

32:58.933 --> 33:00.891
Only I have sergeants'
exams in a month,

33:00.935 --> 33:03.416
and I just have one or two
questions that I'd love to
run by you.

33:03.459 --> 33:04.591
Um...Actually, Constable,

33:04.634 --> 33:06.680
I've just remembered
that I have a, uh...

33:06.723 --> 33:08.856
[DOOR SHUTS]...dentist appointment.

33:08.899 --> 33:11.554
Oh. Sorry, sir.
I didn't know
you were suffering.

33:11.598 --> 33:12.816
Just a routine checkup.

33:12.860 --> 33:14.470
What shall I do, sir?Wait here.

33:14.514 --> 33:16.995
But what if Woolf
turns up, sir?

33:17.038 --> 33:19.475
Won't be long.
And you have
your, uh,

33:19.519 --> 33:20.520
notebook.

33:23.305 --> 33:25.829
Keep your eyes peeled.Yes, sir.

33:25.873 --> 33:26.874
[CLEARS THROAT]

33:33.098 --> 33:34.751
[SIGHS DEEPLY]

33:34.795 --> 33:37.145
[STEALTHY JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

33:55.685 --> 33:56.686
Gin.BARTENDER: Gin?

33:56.730 --> 33:58.036
Yeah, please.

34:09.047 --> 34:10.700
[WHISPERS]
Oh, you're joking.

34:14.139 --> 34:15.227
Oh, no.

34:16.010 --> 34:17.142
[STALKER SIGHS]

34:20.928 --> 34:22.364
[PENCIL SNAPS]Oh, God.

34:24.105 --> 34:25.237
[SIGHS]

34:25.280 --> 34:27.674
[UP-TEMPO JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]

34:40.861 --> 34:42.689
Follow this up
with another, please.

35:07.017 --> 35:08.845
[DOORBELLS RINGING]

35:13.633 --> 35:15.809
[MELODIC WHISTLING]

35:17.550 --> 35:18.942
[STOPS WHISTLING][MUSIC STOPS]

35:24.209 --> 35:25.906
[GRUNTS]

35:25.949 --> 35:27.299
There you are,
Constable.

35:28.952 --> 35:30.998
I've been looking
all over for you.

35:33.914 --> 35:36.264
STOPPARD: So, I gather
it was you that, uh, paid

35:36.308 --> 35:39.963
for Mr. Kopernick's
rather extravagant
hotel suite.

35:40.007 --> 35:42.618
Oh, nothing unusual
in that, Inspector.

35:42.662 --> 35:47.275
I'm afraid a producer
is expected to indulge
the whims of the talent.

35:47.319 --> 35:50.278
Especially when
they're American.

35:50.322 --> 35:53.151
But still,
a pretty penny,
a room at the Savoy.

35:53.194 --> 35:54.500
Par for the course.

35:54.543 --> 35:57.677
When I was in the Congo
for The African Queen,

35:57.720 --> 36:01.811
Huston and Bogart
refused to drink
the water.

36:01.855 --> 36:04.988
Insisted on bourbon,
even to brush their teeth.
[CHUCKLES]

36:05.032 --> 36:08.383
Not so easy to get
hold of in the jungle,
I can assure you.

36:08.427 --> 36:11.995
Huh. You know,
Constable Stalker here is
a great admirer of that film.

36:12.039 --> 36:13.171
Aren't you, Constable?

36:15.695 --> 36:17.305
It's a marvelous film, sir.

36:17.349 --> 36:19.264
Why, thank you, Constable.

36:19.307 --> 36:21.091
[CHUCKLES DRYLY]
Encyclopedia.

36:21.135 --> 36:22.963
Cinematic encyclopedia
up there.

36:23.006 --> 36:24.660
I wouldn't say that.Yeah.

36:24.704 --> 36:26.009
Right.

36:26.053 --> 36:27.446
Being humble.[WOOLF CHUCKLES]

36:27.489 --> 36:28.969
I'm not.

36:29.012 --> 36:31.276
So, it's not true
that Kopernick
had dirt on you?

36:33.930 --> 36:35.149
[SCOFFS]

36:37.325 --> 36:38.979
Who told you that?

36:39.022 --> 36:40.633
[DRUM INTRO MUSIC PLAYING]

36:43.897 --> 36:46.160
[BAND PLAYING UPBEAT MUSIC]

36:48.380 --> 36:49.903
[LIVELY CHATTER]

36:58.303 --> 36:59.913
[ANN CHUCKLING]

36:59.956 --> 37:02.568
Well, now,
what do we
have here?

37:02.611 --> 37:04.570
[ALL CHUCKLE POLITELY]

37:04.613 --> 37:06.572
Huh, Woolfie?

37:06.615 --> 37:08.313
Sittin' in
a quiet corner,

37:08.356 --> 37:10.140
all very nice
and intimate.[ANN CLEARS THROAT]

37:10.706 --> 37:12.317
Hmm?

37:12.360 --> 37:14.667
Say, you wouldn't mind
if I joined you, would you?

37:14.710 --> 37:16.495
[CHUCKLES]
Not at all,
old boy.

37:16.538 --> 37:18.105
Uh-huh.

37:18.148 --> 37:21.500
And you must be
Mrs. Woolf, huh?

37:21.543 --> 37:23.589
Swell to make
your acquaintance.

37:23.632 --> 37:26.505
[MUMBLES]No, no. Leo,
this is Ann.

37:26.548 --> 37:27.984
[CLEARS THROAT]
She's my assistant.

37:28.028 --> 37:29.029
Ah.

37:30.552 --> 37:31.771
Workin' late, huh?

37:33.903 --> 37:35.035
If you'll
excuse me...

37:35.078 --> 37:36.689
Um, I'm sorry.

37:39.431 --> 37:40.736
You have
a nice night, now.

37:43.826 --> 37:45.350
[SIGHS] Well, now.

37:46.655 --> 37:49.615
[TUTS] This puts me
in a tough spot.

37:49.658 --> 37:51.834
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

37:51.878 --> 37:54.272
That I'm afraid I'm gonna
have to take advantage of.

37:56.970 --> 37:59.625
WOOLF: He asked to be put up
at the Savoy, and I agreed.

38:00.539 --> 38:02.976
I knew
it wouldn't be for long.

38:03.019 --> 38:05.544
That is,
just until I found
the right moment to...

38:07.328 --> 38:08.373
tell my wife.

38:10.418 --> 38:13.160
I see. Well,

38:13.203 --> 38:15.162
we'll be in touch
if there's anything else.

38:15.902 --> 38:17.033
Uh...

38:17.860 --> 38:19.209
Constable.

38:19.601 --> 38:20.646
Shall we?

38:28.436 --> 38:30.830
But, sir,
Woolf killed Kopernick
to hush up the affair.

38:30.873 --> 38:32.048
Case closed.

38:32.092 --> 38:33.441
I think if that
was the case,

38:33.485 --> 38:35.051
he wouldn't have
volunteered
the information.

38:36.226 --> 38:38.403
So, then
he's in the clear?

38:38.446 --> 38:39.926
No, not necessarily.

38:39.969 --> 38:41.710
He might have
killed Kopernick for
another reason entirely.

38:42.494 --> 38:45.105
[SIGHS] I tell you,

38:45.148 --> 38:48.630
I'll never get
the hang of this in time
for sergeants' exams.

38:48.674 --> 38:51.067
[KEYS RATTLING][SIGHS DEEPLY]

38:53.983 --> 38:55.333
Constable,
about earlier.

38:55.376 --> 38:57.987
I know it looked like
I'd just come out
of the pub.

38:58.031 --> 38:59.946
You had
just come out
of the pub.

38:59.989 --> 39:01.600
That's right.

39:01.643 --> 39:03.123
But I'd only
gone in there

39:03.166 --> 39:04.864
to get rid of the taste
of the mouthwash.

39:04.907 --> 39:06.605
So you had
a gin, sir.

39:08.041 --> 39:10.043
It's an antiseptic.
I had a filling.

39:10.086 --> 39:12.001
I thought you said
it was a routine checkup.

39:13.829 --> 39:17.050
I see we've read the chapter
on interrogation techniques.

39:17.703 --> 39:19.661
[SIGHS] Sir,

39:19.705 --> 39:22.229
I know I haven't
done anything yet
to impress you

39:22.272 --> 39:26.755
or to inspire
any confidence, and...

39:26.799 --> 39:29.018
I know
you'd probably rather
that I wasn't on the case.

39:29.062 --> 39:32.370
But I didn't ask to be put
on this case either, sir.

39:32.413 --> 39:35.068
I was nervous,
and I still am,

39:35.111 --> 39:36.939
and I'm probably
trying a bit too hard.

39:36.983 --> 39:39.507
But, you know,
even if I do
make mistakes

39:39.551 --> 39:40.943
or if I jump
to conclusions

39:40.987 --> 39:43.903
or talk
a little bit too much,
that has been said,

39:43.946 --> 39:47.994
I just want you to know
that you can trust me.

39:48.995 --> 39:49.996
Sir.

39:54.000 --> 39:56.698
Okay. Good. Um...

40:00.441 --> 40:01.486
[ENGINE STARTS]

40:02.443 --> 40:04.837
[SLOW-TEMPO ROCK SONG PLAYING]

40:50.099 --> 40:51.100
[SWITCH CLICKS]

40:59.761 --> 41:01.937
[MUSIC STOPS ABRUPTLY][ALARM RINGING]

41:05.027 --> 41:06.507
[ALARM STOPS RINGING]

41:06.551 --> 41:07.595
[STOPPARD GROANS]

41:17.257 --> 41:19.389
[WHISPERS]
Oh, you're joking.[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

41:20.303 --> 41:22.392
Constable.Commissioner.

41:22.436 --> 41:23.872
Stoppard about?

41:23.916 --> 41:25.787
Er, no, sir.
He's not yet made it in
this morning.

41:25.831 --> 41:27.223
It's almost eleven o'clock.

41:27.267 --> 41:29.878
He, uh... He had
a dentist appointment, sir.

41:29.922 --> 41:31.663
A filling, I think
he said it was.

41:31.706 --> 41:32.881
A molar,
it might have been?

41:32.925 --> 41:35.623
I have been summoned
to the Home Secretary.

41:35.667 --> 41:37.103
He wants a debrief.

41:37.146 --> 41:38.496
I said
I had good news.

41:43.152 --> 41:44.327
[SIGHS]

41:45.764 --> 41:48.418
Have you seen
the play, sir?Huh?

41:49.594 --> 41:51.421
Oh. Yes.

41:51.465 --> 41:53.423
I'm afraid
I took the wife
for her birthday.

41:53.467 --> 41:54.599
Oh.

41:54.642 --> 41:56.209
Of course,
it didn't fool me
for a moment.

41:56.252 --> 41:57.427
I knew who did it
right away.

41:58.516 --> 42:01.301
[CHUCKLES]She was baffled, though.

42:01.344 --> 42:03.825
Even after the chap
explained everything.

42:03.869 --> 42:06.959
It was a trying night
for all concerned.

42:07.220 --> 42:08.438
Mmm.

42:08.482 --> 42:09.962
I'll stick to flowers
in future.

42:10.005 --> 42:11.833
Yes, always
a safe bet, sir.

42:11.877 --> 42:13.705
[TIRES SCREECH][CAR BUMPS]

42:14.488 --> 42:15.663
STOPPARD: Sorry.

42:15.707 --> 42:16.838
Police.

42:16.882 --> 42:18.710
MAN: Please try to be
more careful, sir.

42:20.625 --> 42:21.974
[CLEARS THROAT]

42:26.413 --> 42:28.502
STOPPARD: Good morning.

42:28.546 --> 42:30.156
Commissioner.Inspector.

42:31.984 --> 42:33.376
Is it wise to eat
so many mints?

42:33.420 --> 42:34.987
STOPPARD: How do
you mean, sir?

42:35.030 --> 42:38.077
Well, haven't you
just been
to the dentist?

42:40.166 --> 42:41.384
Yes, that's right, sir.

42:41.428 --> 42:42.908
Yeah. It was
just a checkup.

42:45.171 --> 42:47.303
Although I did have
a filling as well.

42:48.130 --> 42:50.002
Since I was there.

42:50.045 --> 42:51.786
I've come down here
for an update, Inspector.

42:51.830 --> 42:53.309
We have
good news, sir.

42:53.353 --> 42:54.789
COMMISSIONER AND STOPPARD:
We do?

42:54.833 --> 42:56.748
Yes, sir. Isn't that
what you told
the Home Secretary?

42:56.791 --> 42:59.228
Yes, that's what I told
the Home Secretary

42:59.272 --> 43:00.882
on the telephone.

43:00.926 --> 43:02.492
I came down here
to get it.

43:03.624 --> 43:05.321
So we don't have
good news?

43:05.365 --> 43:06.584
We do have
a witness, sir.

43:06.627 --> 43:07.976
To the murder?[CHUCKLES]

43:08.020 --> 43:10.065
Yeah, that would be nice,
wouldn't it? [CHUCKLES]

43:10.109 --> 43:13.155
Um, no. One of the ushers
saw a suspicious character.

43:13.199 --> 43:14.722
He's waiting
for us inside.

43:15.549 --> 43:17.072
Very well.

43:17.116 --> 43:20.467
I'll tell the Home Secretary
we have a promising lead.

43:20.510 --> 43:22.861
And I'll rely on you
not to make
a liar out of me.

43:23.862 --> 43:25.428
Constable.Commissioner.

43:25.472 --> 43:27.082
Inspector.

43:27.126 --> 43:28.127
Commissioner.

43:30.782 --> 43:31.913
Constable.

43:31.957 --> 43:32.914
Inspector.

43:36.352 --> 43:38.050
STOPPARD: So, Dennis, um,

43:38.093 --> 43:40.313
I understand that
you saw something
the other night.

43:40.356 --> 43:42.402
Yeah.What'd you see?

43:42.445 --> 43:45.274
Well, I'd gone to get
a bottle of Scotch
for the dead man.

43:45.318 --> 43:49.365
Um... This was before,
you know, he died.

43:49.409 --> 43:50.976
Um...And then
you came back,

43:51.019 --> 43:52.934
and that's when you saw
the suspicious character?

43:52.978 --> 43:54.066
Exactly.

43:54.109 --> 43:56.242
Well, sort of.

43:56.285 --> 43:59.071
I didn't get
a very good look,
if I'm honest.

43:59.114 --> 44:02.596
He had on, like,
a darkish overcoat.

44:02.640 --> 44:05.164
I see.
Anything else?

44:05.207 --> 44:06.513
[INHALES SHARPLY]

44:06.556 --> 44:08.863
A pair of trousers.

44:08.907 --> 44:10.691
And a hat.

44:10.735 --> 44:12.519
It was on his head.

44:13.259 --> 44:14.956
Right. Yeah.

44:15.000 --> 44:17.742
Yeah. A soft, felt hat.

44:17.785 --> 44:19.047
Mmm-hmm.

44:19.091 --> 44:20.440
What about
a physical
description?

44:20.483 --> 44:23.399
Was he a tall man?
Short? Thick set?

44:23.443 --> 44:25.619
Oh... Just average,
I'd say.

44:25.663 --> 44:27.882
STOPPARD: Average height
or average build?

44:27.926 --> 44:29.144
Um...

44:29.754 --> 44:30.929
Both?

44:31.843 --> 44:33.105
No, don't ask me.

44:33.148 --> 44:35.107
I don't know.
I'm asking you.

44:36.674 --> 44:38.153
Average height,

44:39.111 --> 44:40.416
medium build.

44:40.460 --> 44:42.505
Would you say
like the Inspector?

44:42.549 --> 44:43.681
DENNIS: Yeah.

44:43.724 --> 44:45.073
Suppose so.
Pretty much.

44:45.117 --> 44:48.468
So what did he do
that made you
suspicious?

44:48.511 --> 44:50.644
It wasn't so much
what he did,

44:50.688 --> 44:53.603
it was more, you know,
the way he did it.

44:54.561 --> 44:56.606
Right.
How'd he do it?

44:56.650 --> 44:58.870
Well, sort of...

45:00.045 --> 45:01.481
suspiciously.

45:05.746 --> 45:07.226
This has been great.

45:07.835 --> 45:09.141
Off you go.

45:10.098 --> 45:11.360
Thank you.Thank you.

45:11.404 --> 45:12.405
Thank you.

45:14.233 --> 45:15.408
That was good.

45:15.451 --> 45:17.802
Do you think
that went well?

45:19.325 --> 45:20.761
STOPPARD: I think it's time
we talk to that actor

45:20.805 --> 45:21.849
who had a fight
with Kopernick.

45:21.893 --> 45:23.329
STALKER:
Mr. Attenborough, sir?

45:23.372 --> 45:25.505
STOPPARD: That's the one.
Famous, is he?

45:25.548 --> 45:28.551
You're pulling my leg, sir.
You've never heard
of Dickie?

45:28.595 --> 45:29.944
Richard Attenborough?

45:29.988 --> 45:32.773
Pinkie Brown?
Brighton Rock?
You must have.

45:32.817 --> 45:34.514
[MIMICKING DICKIE]
"You wanted a recording
of my voice.

45:34.557 --> 45:35.863
"Well, here it is.

45:35.907 --> 45:37.299
"What you want me
to say is
'I love you.'"

45:37.343 --> 45:40.607
Keep in mind
that we're here to
conduct an interview

45:40.650 --> 45:42.087
as part of
a murder
investigation,

45:42.130 --> 45:44.742
not an article for
Sight & Sound
magazine, yes?

45:44.785 --> 45:45.743
Yes, sir.

45:47.222 --> 45:48.920
[KNOCKING]DICKIE: Come in, darling.

45:51.400 --> 45:52.967
Inspector Stoppard.

45:53.011 --> 45:56.014
I say,
a real-life detective.

45:56.057 --> 45:58.146
Scotland Yard
and everything.

45:58.190 --> 45:59.234
And you are?

45:59.713 --> 46:00.975
[CHUCKLES]

46:03.412 --> 46:05.458
This is...[SIGHS IN AWE]

46:05.501 --> 46:07.329
...Constable Stalker.[WHISPERS] Stalker.

46:07.373 --> 46:09.070
[GRUNTS]

46:09.114 --> 46:11.203
Oh, I like the way
you did that.

46:11.246 --> 46:12.944
Very natural.

46:12.987 --> 46:16.295
I hope you don't mind, sir,
but I just want to say bravo.

46:16.338 --> 46:19.559
And, uh, encore.
[CHUCKLING]DICKIE: Oh.

46:19.602 --> 46:20.603
All right,
thank you, Constable.

46:20.647 --> 46:21.953
Yes, thank you,
Constable.

46:21.996 --> 46:23.519
Are you a lover
of theater?

46:23.563 --> 46:24.869
I can get you tickets
if you like.

46:26.174 --> 46:29.090
I would like, sir.
Yes. Very much.

46:29.134 --> 46:31.397
DICKIE: It would be good
to get a professional take
on it.

46:31.440 --> 46:32.441
STALKER: Mmm-hmm.DICKIE: Yeah.

46:32.485 --> 46:33.965
I have
so many questions.

46:34.008 --> 46:35.662
I have one or two
of my own.

46:35.705 --> 46:38.273
I dare say
that you do.

46:38.317 --> 46:41.102
I understand
that you and,
uh, Kopernick

46:41.146 --> 46:43.191
came to blows
the night in question.

46:43.235 --> 46:46.020
Was there
a particular reason
for the ill feeling?

46:46.064 --> 46:48.762
Tell me, Inspector,
did you get your limp
during the war?

46:51.591 --> 46:52.635
It's very slight.

46:52.679 --> 46:54.159
I noticed it
the other night

46:54.202 --> 46:56.422
when you were on stage.
I, um... [TUTS]

46:56.465 --> 46:59.207
Well, I thought
I might borrow it,
if you don't mind.

46:59.251 --> 47:02.515
It's always good
for the lead character
to have a physical defect.

47:02.558 --> 47:05.648
Speaks to
a troubled soul.

47:05.692 --> 47:08.869
It was me, Inspector.
You need look
no further.

47:08.913 --> 47:09.957
I arrest you

47:10.001 --> 47:11.219
for the murder of Leo...No, no, no.

47:11.263 --> 47:12.525
No. Not yet.

47:12.568 --> 47:14.005
STALKER: Oh. Sorry, sir.

47:14.048 --> 47:16.746
I was
the particular reason
for the ill feeling.

47:16.790 --> 47:19.401
Yes, well,
Leo had his eye
on Sheila, you see.

47:19.445 --> 47:20.489
And I took exception.

47:20.533 --> 47:22.317
He was a real hound,
Inspector.

47:23.275 --> 47:26.147
[DRAMATIC MUSIC INTRO PLAYING]

47:26.191 --> 47:28.062
LEO: Come on,
play nice.

47:28.106 --> 47:29.063
Maybe I can help you.

47:29.934 --> 47:31.109
Help me?

47:31.152 --> 47:32.762
To do what?

47:32.806 --> 47:35.069
Bag the lead role
in the film of
The Mousetrap.

47:36.679 --> 47:37.985
Top billing.

47:38.029 --> 47:39.117
Make you a star.

47:39.160 --> 47:41.641
But I have bagged
the lead role.

47:41.684 --> 47:43.251
Yeah, who told
you that, Woolfie?

47:43.295 --> 47:45.079
He is the producer.

47:45.123 --> 47:46.951
Honey, he just
cuts the checks.

47:46.994 --> 47:48.343
I'm the director.

47:48.387 --> 47:50.780
Without me,
there is no movie.
You understand?

47:50.824 --> 47:52.608
You got
a problem, buddy?

47:54.045 --> 47:56.221
Keep the change.
And the glass.

47:56.264 --> 47:58.788
And the studio,
don't they have
a say in it?

47:58.832 --> 48:02.053
Rumor is
they want to put
a name in the picture

48:02.096 --> 48:04.533
that people have
heard of.

48:04.577 --> 48:07.014
Bona fide
Hollywood star.

48:07.058 --> 48:09.582
They like Grace Kelly.
You ever heard of her?

48:13.238 --> 48:14.500
Don't worry.

48:15.544 --> 48:17.024
They can be
talked round.

48:18.243 --> 48:21.463
I've got a very,
uh, silver tongue.

48:22.334 --> 48:24.466
[MUSIC BUILDS UP]

48:24.510 --> 48:26.686
[DICKIE GRUNTS][GUESTS EXCLAIM]

48:26.729 --> 48:27.948
SHEILA: I won't lie,
Inspector.

48:27.992 --> 48:29.863
I was not entirely sorry
to learn of his demise,

48:29.907 --> 48:31.952
but I had
no part in it.

48:31.996 --> 48:34.346
Much like the film adaptation
of The Mousetrap,
it would seem.

48:34.389 --> 48:35.913
Oh, come now, darling,
you don't know that.

48:35.956 --> 48:38.002
Woolf promised you
the role.

48:38.045 --> 48:40.134
He's a man of his word.
He went to Eton.

48:40.178 --> 48:41.831
[SCOFFS]
Wake up, Dickie.

48:41.875 --> 48:43.833
He's a man of
whatever word will
get his film made.

48:43.877 --> 48:47.620
And that contract business
with Choo is coming
apart at the seams.

48:47.663 --> 48:49.274
Choo?Bless you, sir.

48:49.317 --> 48:51.711
No, as in
Petula Spencer.

48:51.754 --> 48:53.974
She sold Woolf
the film rights.

48:54.018 --> 48:55.671
Well, about
those tickets.

48:55.715 --> 48:57.151
Is there a day
that suits you better?

48:57.195 --> 49:00.024
Uh, I'm generally free
on Tuesdays
and Wednesdays.

49:00.067 --> 49:01.112
And Thursdays.

49:01.155 --> 49:03.201
Well, thank you, sir.
Thank you, madam.

49:03.244 --> 49:04.942
No, no, not at all.
We'll be sure
to let you know

49:04.985 --> 49:06.856
if anything else
springs to mind.

49:06.900 --> 49:09.685
I'm sure it's always
the insignificant detail

49:09.729 --> 49:11.774
that catches
the killer
in the end.

49:11.818 --> 49:12.950
Isn't that so,
Inspector?

49:16.605 --> 49:20.392
I don't usually
have a lot on
on weekends either.

49:20.435 --> 49:22.960
Or Mondays.
For the...
For the tickets.

49:23.003 --> 49:24.091
STOPPARD: Constable.Sir.

49:24.135 --> 49:25.179
Right.

49:25.223 --> 49:27.355
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

49:28.226 --> 49:29.879
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

49:34.101 --> 49:35.755
[DOG WHIMPERING]

49:59.431 --> 50:00.693
She'll see you now.

50:02.347 --> 50:04.479
STOPPARD: So, you own
this theater?

50:04.523 --> 50:06.525
Yes. Humble
beginnings.

50:06.568 --> 50:07.830
[RAGTIME PIANO MUSIC PLAYING]

50:07.874 --> 50:09.267
You'll have to
excuse Mother.

50:09.310 --> 50:11.834
She's not been herself
since Father died,

50:11.878 --> 50:14.011
in the first
Great War.

50:14.054 --> 50:16.622
It's been
a long 30 years.

50:16.665 --> 50:18.537
It's nice that
you gave her a job.

50:18.580 --> 50:21.105
Well, how else is she
gonna pay the rent?

50:21.148 --> 50:23.846
I let her have
the spare room
at a discount as it is.

50:23.890 --> 50:26.197
Yes, no.
You can stop there.

50:26.240 --> 50:29.287
We get the idea. Bravo.[PIANO MUSIC STOPS]

50:29.330 --> 50:31.115
I understand that
you handled the sale

50:31.158 --> 50:33.291
of The Mousetrap
film rights
to John Woolf?

50:33.334 --> 50:35.771
Yes, that's right.
I did. Wait... Why?

50:36.685 --> 50:37.860
What's he been saying?

50:38.731 --> 50:41.255
Oh, he's such a crybaby.

50:41.299 --> 50:44.258
Honestly, he acts as though
I put a gun to his head.

50:44.302 --> 50:45.999
[SUSPENSEFUL NOTE PLAYS]

50:46.043 --> 50:47.087
[POPS]

50:47.131 --> 50:48.393
ANN AND PETULA: Oh! [LAUGHING]

50:48.436 --> 50:50.351
Hang on a minute.
Is this important?

50:50.395 --> 50:51.961
I doubt it.
What does it say?

50:52.005 --> 50:54.486
"No motion picture
based on the stage play
The Mousetrap

50:54.529 --> 50:55.922
"is to enter
into production

50:55.965 --> 50:58.055
"until a minimum
of six months
have elapsed

50:58.098 --> 51:00.100
"since the end
of its first
theatrical run."

51:00.144 --> 51:01.928
Oh, you don't
need to worry
about that.

51:01.971 --> 51:03.190
It's a whodunit.

51:03.234 --> 51:04.409
As soon as
word gets out
who did do it,

51:04.452 --> 51:06.150
audiences are
bound to drop off.

51:06.193 --> 51:09.979
Come on, sign on
the dotted line,
and I'll make a toast.

51:10.023 --> 51:11.285
[ANN AND PETULA CHUCKLE]

51:14.288 --> 51:16.725
Ann, darling,
the next contract
I sign

51:16.769 --> 51:18.640
will be our
marriage certificate.

51:18.684 --> 51:21.295
[CHUCKLES]Well, first it'll be
the divorce papers.

51:21.339 --> 51:23.471
But then
our marriage
certificate.

51:25.517 --> 51:27.345
[ANN YELPS]Edana, darling.

51:28.433 --> 51:29.477
What a pleasant surprise.

51:29.521 --> 51:32.001
You know Choo
and, uh...Mmm-hmm.

51:32.045 --> 51:33.394
...Ann.I do.

51:33.438 --> 51:35.092
Dear girl, what on Earth
are you doing down there?

51:35.135 --> 51:38.399
I just fell over.
Excuse me.

51:38.443 --> 51:41.272
Honestly, it's like
having Buster Keaton
for an assistant.

51:41.315 --> 51:43.056
Now, I've just come
from Madame Zena...

51:43.100 --> 51:45.058
Oh, darling,
I really wish
you wouldn't see that...

51:45.102 --> 51:46.233
Please don't call her
a charlatan.

51:46.277 --> 51:47.321
I was going to say
"crackpot."

51:51.412 --> 51:53.371
What's this?EDANA: It's a Tarot card.

51:53.414 --> 51:55.068
I can see that.
What does it mean?

51:55.808 --> 51:56.852
Betrayal.

51:56.896 --> 51:58.898
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

52:02.728 --> 52:03.946
Ooh.

52:03.990 --> 52:06.471
Betrayal as in
his affair,
not the contract.

52:06.514 --> 52:08.864
That was above board.
Is above board.

52:08.908 --> 52:11.432
Agatha insisted on
that clause, not me.

52:11.476 --> 52:14.870
No, she's fiercely protective
of her own work, you see,
because...

52:14.914 --> 52:16.785
Well, she has to be.

52:16.829 --> 52:18.744
People get so riled up.

52:18.787 --> 52:20.572
She's had death threats,
you know.

52:20.615 --> 52:23.618
Poor girl can't write
so much as a letter
to The Times

52:23.662 --> 52:25.403
without a deluge
of legal action

52:25.446 --> 52:28.928
and spurious claims
she stole this plot
or that character.

52:28.971 --> 52:30.843
Isn't that what
happened here,
though?

52:30.886 --> 52:34.368
Isn't The Mousetrap
based on a true story?

52:34.412 --> 52:38.242
Yes. Well, originally.
I mean, tangentially.

52:38.285 --> 52:39.808
In any case,
that's the reason

52:39.852 --> 52:42.985
Woolf was so keen
to shut the theater
the other night.

52:43.029 --> 52:44.422
He can't make his film

52:44.465 --> 52:47.207
until the play
ends its run
in the West End.

52:47.251 --> 52:50.471
As it is, what with
the play being such
a phenomenal success,

52:50.515 --> 52:53.474
he's stuck in
theatrical purgatory.

52:53.518 --> 52:54.606
Mmm-hmm.

52:54.649 --> 52:57.174
He's a ruthless
customer, is Woolf.

52:57.217 --> 52:59.741
He'll stop at nothing
to get his film made.

53:06.008 --> 53:07.445
STALKER: It's definitely
Woolf, sir.

53:08.315 --> 53:10.491
Well, not 100%.

53:10.535 --> 53:14.887
More like 73-74%,
I'd say.

53:14.930 --> 53:18.673
He killed Kopernick
in the theater
to force it to close down

53:18.717 --> 53:20.545
so that he could
make his film.

53:20.588 --> 53:22.634
He could marry
his mistress.

53:22.677 --> 53:24.505
And then
he could get shot
of a blackmailer.

53:24.549 --> 53:26.290
It's not Woolf.
It's too elaborate.

53:26.333 --> 53:28.422
Burn the place down,
if that's what you want.

53:28.466 --> 53:31.773
Besides, doesn't he need
a director to make a film?

53:31.817 --> 53:33.340
Well, then it's back
to Cocker-Norris.

53:33.384 --> 53:34.689
Process of
elimination.

53:35.516 --> 53:36.952
No, it's not
Mervyn.

53:36.996 --> 53:39.564
Yeah, but
the tongue
business.

53:39.607 --> 53:41.479
And he clearly
didn't like Leo,
did he?

53:44.395 --> 53:46.135
People don't rip out
other people's tongues

53:46.179 --> 53:47.398
because of
creative differences.

53:47.441 --> 53:49.922
They do it
out of revenge

53:49.965 --> 53:51.663
or rage because
they've lost
a loved one.

53:51.706 --> 53:53.055
They can't forgive
or forget,

53:53.099 --> 53:55.362
so they just stew
and fester
alone in the dark

53:55.406 --> 53:56.624
until finally
it all comes out

53:56.668 --> 53:59.105
in a sudden,
frenzied act
of violence.

54:04.763 --> 54:06.460
How did you get
the limp, sir?

54:06.504 --> 54:08.070
If you don't mind
me asking.

54:08.114 --> 54:11.117
Uh, in the war.
Got shot
in the Italian Alps.

54:11.160 --> 54:12.161
Hmm.

54:13.728 --> 54:14.903
Sounds painful.

54:16.383 --> 54:18.429
What do you...
[LAUGHS]

54:18.472 --> 54:20.822
[CHUCKLES]
Sorry, sir.

54:20.866 --> 54:22.998
No, that's very funny.

54:24.739 --> 54:27.525
Is there
a Mr. Stalker,
Stalker?

54:27.568 --> 54:29.831
Uh, I'm afraid he died
in the war, sir.

54:31.746 --> 54:32.878
Children?

54:32.921 --> 54:34.401
A boy
and a girl.

54:34.445 --> 54:36.534
Can't be easy.[CHUCKLES]

54:36.577 --> 54:39.319
What about you?
Do you have
any family, sir?

54:39.363 --> 54:42.061
[SMACKS LIPS] Uh,
I came close, once.

54:42.104 --> 54:43.889
Yeah, I had
an unfaithful wife.

54:43.932 --> 54:45.717
Oh.

54:45.760 --> 54:47.022
She was
eight months pregnant

54:47.066 --> 54:48.459
when she told me
I wasn't the father.

54:50.722 --> 54:52.767
I'd made a cot
and everything.

54:53.942 --> 54:56.118
That's awful, sir.
I'm sorry.

54:57.337 --> 54:59.383
[GRUNTS DISMISSIVELY]

54:59.426 --> 55:01.210
Landlord.LANDLORD: Yes, sir?

55:01.254 --> 55:02.603
Another round.

55:02.647 --> 55:03.691
Oh, I don't know.

55:03.735 --> 55:05.998
Should we maybe
get going, sir?

55:06.041 --> 55:07.521
Got work tomorrow.
[CHUCKLES]

55:07.565 --> 55:10.219
[MELLOW MUSIC PLAYING][DOOR OPENS]

55:10.263 --> 55:12.874
LANDLORD: Go on, steer off
before I call the police!

55:12.918 --> 55:13.919
[STALKER GRUNTS]

55:14.833 --> 55:17.357
Sorry again.
Thank you.

55:17.401 --> 55:19.316
Are you sure
you're all right
to drive, sir?

55:19.359 --> 55:20.534
Absolutely.

55:20.578 --> 55:21.796
STALKER: Oh!

55:21.840 --> 55:23.711
STOPPARD: I could
run you home if you like.

55:24.756 --> 55:27.324
[MELLOW MUSIC CONTINUES]

55:37.769 --> 55:41.686
STALKER: Now.
Just gonna
pop you there.

55:41.729 --> 55:43.557
[SLURRING] I can
take it from here,
Constable.

55:47.256 --> 55:48.562
Oh.

55:48.606 --> 55:49.607
Sir.

55:56.265 --> 55:57.266
There we go.

56:02.663 --> 56:04.186
[PANTING]

56:08.887 --> 56:10.932
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

56:40.701 --> 56:41.833
[SWITCH CLICKS]

56:48.535 --> 56:50.972
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

56:56.064 --> 56:58.066
[MUSIC INTENSIFYING]

57:06.945 --> 57:07.989
[MUSIC FADES]

57:13.386 --> 57:14.518
Morning, sir.

57:15.693 --> 57:17.434
What do you want?

57:17.477 --> 57:21.002
Uh, the other night, sir.
The dead Yank.

57:21.046 --> 57:24.005
Inspector Stoppard
got the call and not
Leeke or Priestley.

57:24.919 --> 57:25.920
So?

57:32.274 --> 57:34.276
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

57:35.713 --> 57:38.019
Leeke was in Skegness
on his honeymoon,

57:38.063 --> 57:40.065
and Priestley took
the Rillington Place call.

57:42.328 --> 57:43.329
What time?

57:44.983 --> 57:48.073
Half-past 11:00.
Book at Bedtimewas on.

57:53.948 --> 57:56.298
Did you ever meet
Stoppard's wife, sir?

57:57.082 --> 57:58.344
I did.

57:58.387 --> 58:00.128
You don't happen
to remember
her name, do you?

58:07.309 --> 58:08.441
It was...

58:10.530 --> 58:12.184
Mrs. Stoppard.

58:14.882 --> 58:15.883
Brilliant.

58:21.193 --> 58:23.151
[ROUSING MUSIC PLAYING]

58:33.422 --> 58:34.946
Hello, is this Abigale?

58:37.122 --> 58:38.384
Hello, is this Beryl?

58:38.427 --> 58:40.560
I am a friend
of Leo Kopernick's.

58:40.604 --> 58:41.953
[LINE DISCONNECTS]

58:41.996 --> 58:42.997
Beryl?

58:44.651 --> 58:46.523
Is Geraldine there
by any chance?

58:47.524 --> 58:48.568
[SIGHS]

59:13.898 --> 59:15.900
STOPPARD:
Oh, Constable.STALKER: Sir.

59:15.943 --> 59:18.293
Did Dickie ever
come through on
those theater tickets?

59:18.337 --> 59:21.775
I thought of going,
and, uh...
Maybe the play's the thing

59:21.819 --> 59:25.300
Ties this all together.
Would you like
to tag along?

59:25.344 --> 59:26.693
Yes, sir. Um...[DOOR OPENS]

59:28.826 --> 59:30.305
What is it, Constable?

59:30.349 --> 59:32.003
Uh, nothing, sir.Oh.

59:32.960 --> 59:35.833
Do you, um,
want a cup of tea?

59:35.876 --> 59:38.575
[SIGHS] Listen
to me, Stalker.

59:38.618 --> 59:42.579
No one is ever going to
take you seriously
as a police officer

59:42.622 --> 59:44.276
if you act like
a tea-lady,
do you hear me?

59:44.319 --> 59:45.799
Yes, sir.
Thank you, sir.
[CHUCKLES]

59:45.843 --> 59:47.322
Milk and two sugars.

59:51.849 --> 59:52.893
Commissioner.

59:52.937 --> 59:55.983
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:00:00.422 --> 1:00:01.815
I said,
"Who do you want?

1:00:01.859 --> 1:00:04.644
"Agatha Christie or
Mervyn Cocker-Norris?

1:00:04.688 --> 1:00:07.516
"Anyone can do her,
but only I can do me."

1:00:07.560 --> 1:00:09.867
GIO: Stronzo.
[MUTTERS INDISTINCTLY]

1:00:09.910 --> 1:00:13.610
MERVYN: The Mousetrap
in the house style,
as it were.

1:00:13.653 --> 1:00:15.394
I'll take
the bare bones
of the story,

1:00:15.437 --> 1:00:19.224
a rather mundane tale
of child abuse,
and make it my own.

1:00:23.097 --> 1:00:24.708
Here we are.

1:00:24.751 --> 1:00:27.275
Oh. These aren't
together, sir.

1:00:27.319 --> 1:00:28.581
Oh.

1:00:28.625 --> 1:00:30.627
Well, we can cover
more ground that way.

1:00:30.670 --> 1:00:31.802
Keep your eyes peeled.

1:00:31.845 --> 1:00:33.499
Yes, sir.

1:00:33.542 --> 1:00:35.196
[AUDIENCE CHATTERING]

1:00:40.549 --> 1:00:42.551
[ROUSING MUSIC PLAYING]

1:00:43.335 --> 1:00:44.466
STOPPARD: Cheers.

1:00:55.303 --> 1:00:56.304
[MUSIC FADES]

1:00:57.305 --> 1:00:58.263
SHEILA: [AS MOLLIE] Hello?

1:01:01.658 --> 1:01:03.398
Hello?

1:01:03.442 --> 1:01:05.749
Is anyone there?[PHONE RINGING]

1:01:05.792 --> 1:01:08.055
MRS. BOYLE: Who's calling
at this late hour?

1:01:09.274 --> 1:01:10.275
MOLLIE: Yes?

1:01:10.884 --> 1:01:11.842
All right then.

1:01:12.973 --> 1:01:14.758
That was Scotland Yard.

1:01:14.801 --> 1:01:16.890
They're sending out
an inspector.

1:01:16.934 --> 1:01:19.937
In this
unseasonable
blizzard?

1:01:19.980 --> 1:01:22.243
What on Earth for?[MOLLIE SCREAMS]

1:01:22.287 --> 1:01:23.810
[GASPS]MAJOR METCALF: Good Lord.

1:01:25.725 --> 1:01:26.813
MOLLIE: Inspector.

1:01:26.857 --> 1:01:27.858
DICKIE: [AS TROTTER]
Thank you.

1:01:29.381 --> 1:01:30.382
Good evening.

1:01:32.645 --> 1:01:34.908
I am Detective
Sergeant Trotter.

1:01:35.779 --> 1:01:37.302
Please excuse
the limp.

1:01:37.345 --> 1:01:40.261
An old war wound
playing up in the cold.

1:01:40.305 --> 1:01:42.786
I'm assuming
you were warned
of my arrival?

1:01:44.309 --> 1:01:47.660
Apropos of nothing,
I'm a magistrate.

1:01:47.704 --> 1:01:50.576
Also, he looks
too young to be
an inspector.

1:01:50.619 --> 1:01:53.753
Well, I'm old enough
to remember
the Corrigan Case.

1:01:53.797 --> 1:01:57.278
Yes, a dreadful
business.

1:01:57.322 --> 1:02:01.892
Two brothers
who put their faith in
the British social services.

1:02:01.935 --> 1:02:04.982
A sorry tale of abuse
that ended in tragedy.

1:02:06.592 --> 1:02:08.202
Yes, it was
in all of the papers.

1:02:08.246 --> 1:02:09.943
MERVYN: [SOFTLY]
Gio, I can't
sit through this again.

1:02:09.987 --> 1:02:11.945
I'm sorry.
Will you excuse me?

1:02:11.989 --> 1:02:16.863
TROTTER: One died,
the other left traumatized.

1:02:16.907 --> 1:02:19.387
I shudder to think
what an ordeal like that

1:02:19.431 --> 1:02:21.215
might do to
a vulnerable mind.

1:02:21.259 --> 1:02:22.303
[WHISPERS]
Won't be a moment.

1:02:22.347 --> 1:02:23.914
I'm just going to try
and catch Mervyn.

1:02:23.957 --> 1:02:25.785
MOLLIE: Oh, bother.
I forgot the tea.

1:02:25.829 --> 1:02:27.918
TROTTER: By God,
that has to be

1:02:27.961 --> 1:02:30.529
the worst cup of tea
I've ever had.

1:02:30.572 --> 1:02:32.052
[AUDIENCE CHUCKLES]

1:02:32.096 --> 1:02:34.359
MRS. BOYLE: I agree.

1:02:34.402 --> 1:02:37.841
Did you make it
in a teapot
or a plant pot?

1:02:37.884 --> 1:02:39.103
STOPPARD: Pardon me.

1:02:39.146 --> 1:02:40.321
Excuse me. Thank you. Sorry.MOLLIE: Oh, dear.

1:02:40.365 --> 1:02:41.801
Pardon me.
Excuse me.
Sorry.

1:02:41.845 --> 1:02:44.761
MOLLIE: I've already had
another disaster
in the kitchen.

1:02:44.804 --> 1:02:48.068
I left out the steak pieces
in my steak and kidney pie.

1:02:49.461 --> 1:02:51.071
Gloves.

1:02:51.115 --> 1:02:52.812
MOLLIE: Kidney pie
just doesn't have
the same ring to it.

1:02:52.856 --> 1:02:54.466
Sorry.
Excuse me.
Pardon me.

1:02:54.509 --> 1:02:55.684
Excuse me.
Terribly sorry.

1:02:56.816 --> 1:02:58.600
Bleeding gloves.
I'm so sorry.

1:02:58.644 --> 1:03:00.254
There they are.
Thank you.

1:03:00.298 --> 1:03:02.039
Sorry. Sorry.
Terribly sorry.

1:03:02.082 --> 1:03:03.257
MAJOR METCALF:
I'm beginning to think

1:03:03.301 --> 1:03:04.215
it was
a dreadful mistake
to skip lunch.

1:03:04.258 --> 1:03:05.433
STOPPARD: Excuse me.

1:03:06.783 --> 1:03:08.610
MOLLIE: I'll open
a tin of peas.

1:03:10.787 --> 1:03:12.919
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:03:45.299 --> 1:03:47.867
ANNOUNCER: [ON RADIO]
We interruptBook at Bedtime

1:03:47.911 --> 1:03:51.566
to warn residents
in the Colney Hatch area
of London

1:03:51.610 --> 1:03:54.961
to be on the lookout
for an escaped lunatic.

1:03:55.005 --> 1:03:56.180
[SWITCH THUDS][GASPS]

1:04:00.401 --> 1:04:01.750
[SWITCH THUDS]Hmm.

1:04:03.578 --> 1:04:06.581
[WHISTLING THREE BLIND MICE]

1:04:10.672 --> 1:04:11.760
[GASPS]

1:04:11.804 --> 1:04:14.589
[SIGHS IN RELIEF]
You startled me.

1:04:14.633 --> 1:04:16.765
[GASPS, CHUCKLES]
You startled me.

1:04:16.809 --> 1:04:18.550
[OMINOUS MUSIC PLAYING]

1:04:18.593 --> 1:04:20.726
[CHOKES][MRS. BOYLE GASPS, GRUNTS]

1:04:23.120 --> 1:04:24.208
[MERVYN GRUNTS]

1:04:24.251 --> 1:04:25.774
[STRAINING]

1:04:28.255 --> 1:04:30.562
[BOTH CHOKING]

1:04:33.565 --> 1:04:34.740
[MERVYN GRUNTS]

1:04:34.783 --> 1:04:36.960
[MUSIC RISING]

1:04:37.003 --> 1:04:38.918
[DRAMATIC END NOTE PLAYING]

1:04:46.447 --> 1:04:47.448
[MUSIC FADES]

1:04:52.627 --> 1:04:54.020
Turn the lights on.

1:04:54.064 --> 1:04:56.805
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING][SWITCHES CLICKING]

1:04:59.286 --> 1:05:00.766
[SCREAMS]

1:05:01.593 --> 1:05:04.161
[AUDIENCE APPLAUDING]

1:05:05.989 --> 1:05:07.077
[DOOR OPENS]

1:05:07.120 --> 1:05:08.643
[AUDIENCE CHATTERING]

1:05:09.644 --> 1:05:11.168
[WOMEN SCREAMING]

1:05:12.212 --> 1:05:14.171
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

1:05:19.350 --> 1:05:21.439
Stop in the name
of the law!

1:05:31.492 --> 1:05:33.233
[GRUNTS] Bollocks!

1:05:35.844 --> 1:05:37.281
[INDISTINCT CHATTER]

1:05:37.324 --> 1:05:39.065
DICKIE: Well,
that's a good thing.

1:05:39.109 --> 1:05:40.414
The limp,
was it too much?
[GRUNTS]

1:05:41.938 --> 1:05:43.678
Oh.Oh, God.

1:05:43.722 --> 1:05:45.854
Oh, sorry, sir.
I thought you were
somebody else.

1:05:45.898 --> 1:05:47.334
No, no, it's all right.

1:05:47.378 --> 1:05:48.814
And thank you
for the tickets.

1:05:48.857 --> 1:05:49.902
Very welcome.

1:05:54.428 --> 1:05:56.039
[MUSIC HALTS]

1:05:57.388 --> 1:05:59.999
[CAT MEOWING IN DISTANCE]

1:06:02.219 --> 1:06:03.568
[STALKER YELLS]

1:06:03.611 --> 1:06:04.612
[THUMP]

1:06:06.484 --> 1:06:08.921
[GASPING]

1:06:13.447 --> 1:06:14.579
[GROANS]

1:06:14.622 --> 1:06:18.017
[EERIE MUSIC PLAYING]

1:06:18.061 --> 1:06:20.367
[FOOTSTEPS CRUNCHING ON SNOW][SOFT ANIMALS' CALLS]

1:06:24.850 --> 1:06:25.894
[BOTTLES CLINK]

1:06:29.289 --> 1:06:30.725
[RATTLING]

1:06:36.340 --> 1:06:37.645
[SIGHS]

1:06:39.952 --> 1:06:41.345
LEO: There ya go.

1:06:41.388 --> 1:06:42.607
Bottoms up.

1:06:42.650 --> 1:06:43.651
Cheers.

1:06:45.392 --> 1:06:47.307
[EERIE MUSIC CONTINUES]

1:06:48.874 --> 1:06:50.571
What brings you
to this neck of the woods?

1:06:50.615 --> 1:06:52.617
Oh, a murder investigation.

1:06:52.660 --> 1:06:54.880
Yeah? Anyone I know?

1:06:56.186 --> 1:06:57.274
You.

1:06:57.317 --> 1:06:58.318
[MUSIC HALTS]

1:06:59.015 --> 1:07:00.016
[SWALLOWS]

1:07:00.886 --> 1:07:02.366
I'm sorry, I thought...

1:07:02.409 --> 1:07:04.368
No, no, no.
It's all right.
It's all right. Uh...

1:07:05.978 --> 1:07:07.719
Say, uh, Inspector.

1:07:09.112 --> 1:07:11.636
Tell me,
was anyone, uh...

1:07:13.420 --> 1:07:15.814
you know,
sad to see me go?

1:07:19.992 --> 1:07:20.993
Ah.

1:07:22.342 --> 1:07:23.300
Figures.

1:07:31.612 --> 1:07:33.353
I'm sorry, sir,
you can't go
in there.

1:07:33.397 --> 1:07:34.572
Ah...

1:07:34.615 --> 1:07:36.052
You can only go in
if you have a ticket.

1:07:36.095 --> 1:07:38.576
I had a ticket.
It was in my pocket.

1:07:38.619 --> 1:07:42.275
That's... I could have
sworn I had on
a pair of trousers.

1:07:42.319 --> 1:07:43.537
I had trousers on.

1:07:45.365 --> 1:07:46.453
Where's my ticket?

1:07:46.497 --> 1:07:47.976
[SIGHS]I'm sorry, sir.

1:07:48.020 --> 1:07:49.587
I can't let you in
unless you have
a ticket.

1:07:49.630 --> 1:07:52.024
I had a ticket.
I just don't
have it on me.

1:07:52.068 --> 1:07:54.157
Let me in!
Stop mucking about.

1:07:54.200 --> 1:07:55.680
I've gotta go in.No, please, sir.

1:07:55.723 --> 1:07:58.596
[MAN WHISTLING
THREE BLIND MICE]

1:07:58.639 --> 1:07:59.945
You. I know you.

1:08:01.599 --> 1:08:02.687
What are you doing?

1:08:02.730 --> 1:08:04.341
[TENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

1:08:04.384 --> 1:08:06.256
STALKER: Sir. Sir.

1:08:06.299 --> 1:08:07.518
[MUSIC STOPS]I've got a ticket!

1:08:12.784 --> 1:08:14.090
The hell
is going on?

1:08:17.789 --> 1:08:19.007
What am I
doing here?

1:08:19.965 --> 1:08:21.619
What happened
to my trousers?

1:08:21.662 --> 1:08:23.142
You asked me
to press them, sir.

1:08:23.186 --> 1:08:24.230
I did?

1:08:24.274 --> 1:08:25.536
Yes, sir.
You were adamant.

1:08:28.495 --> 1:08:29.888
How long
have I been here?

1:08:30.454 --> 1:08:31.498
Eighteen hours.

1:08:33.457 --> 1:08:35.328
[GROANS]

1:08:35.372 --> 1:08:37.678
[GRUNTS]
My head is
killing me.

1:08:37.722 --> 1:08:39.332
It's bloody
freezing
in here.

1:08:41.465 --> 1:08:42.596
Did you make
an arrest?

1:08:44.163 --> 1:08:45.860
We did.

1:08:45.904 --> 1:08:47.688
Who was it?
Was it Gio?

1:08:47.732 --> 1:08:49.386
Gio?

1:08:49.429 --> 1:08:52.867
Yeah, Gio. The...
The Italian chap,
the killer.

1:08:52.911 --> 1:08:55.783
The man in
a darkish overcoat,
soft felt hat...

1:08:55.827 --> 1:08:57.437
I chased out
the theater.

1:08:57.481 --> 1:08:59.265
Inspector,
that man was you.

1:08:59.657 --> 1:09:01.093
What?

1:09:01.137 --> 1:09:04.227
You are the man
in the darkish overcoat

1:09:04.270 --> 1:09:07.969
and the soft felt hat
that Constable Stalker here

1:09:08.013 --> 1:09:09.536
chased from the theater.

1:09:10.842 --> 1:09:13.714
I'm sorry,
I'm not following.

1:09:13.758 --> 1:09:15.629
I think I might have
a concussion.

1:09:15.673 --> 1:09:16.804
Or the shakes?

1:09:18.415 --> 1:09:20.373
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:09:22.027 --> 1:09:23.681
STOPPARD: No,
this is ridiculous.

1:09:23.724 --> 1:09:25.944
What possible reason

1:09:25.987 --> 1:09:27.859
could I have
for strangling
a playwright?

1:09:27.902 --> 1:09:30.340
I haven't seen
anything he's done.

1:09:30.383 --> 1:09:34.039
No, but Mervyn saw the woman
who visited Kopernick
at the Savoy.

1:09:34.996 --> 1:09:36.694
So?

1:09:36.737 --> 1:09:40.611
Inspector,
have you spoken
to Joyce lately?

1:09:41.264 --> 1:09:42.526
Joyce?

1:09:42.569 --> 1:09:43.657
Your wife.

1:09:43.701 --> 1:09:44.876
Ex-wife.

1:09:44.919 --> 1:09:47.183
Yes. I met her once
at a police social.

1:09:47.226 --> 1:09:50.011
A plain girl.

1:09:50.055 --> 1:09:51.317
Very homely.

1:09:51.361 --> 1:09:53.667
What does Joyce
have to do
with anything?

1:09:53.711 --> 1:09:56.931
Uh, her name was in Leo's
little black book, sir.

1:09:56.975 --> 1:09:58.194
Oh, come on.
You don't...

1:09:58.237 --> 1:10:00.283
You don't seriously think
that Leo and...

1:10:00.326 --> 1:10:02.894
COMMISSIONER:
Didn't your wife
leave you for a Yank?

1:10:02.937 --> 1:10:05.766
Leo was an American G.I.

1:10:05.810 --> 1:10:08.465
Will you listen to yourselves?
You hear what you're sayin'?

1:10:09.814 --> 1:10:10.815
Constable.

1:10:16.516 --> 1:10:18.953
"They do it
out of revenge
or rage

1:10:18.997 --> 1:10:23.436
"because they have
lost a loved one and
can't forgive or forget.

1:10:23.480 --> 1:10:25.917
"So they just stew and fester

1:10:25.960 --> 1:10:29.573
"until it all comes out
in a sudden, frenzied
act of violence."

1:10:32.358 --> 1:10:34.012
You wrote that down.

1:10:37.233 --> 1:10:40.627
That was
a private conversation.

1:10:40.671 --> 1:10:42.716
Well, I thought
it could be
important, sir.

1:10:44.152 --> 1:10:45.502
STOPPARD: Unbelievable.

1:10:48.200 --> 1:10:49.506
We found her.

1:10:49.549 --> 1:10:50.985
Who?Joyce.

1:10:51.029 --> 1:10:52.726
Joyce.
Joyce is here?

1:10:52.770 --> 1:10:53.771
Constable.

1:10:57.340 --> 1:10:59.472
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC
INTENSIFYING]

1:11:11.484 --> 1:11:12.529
[MUSIC STOPS]

1:11:12.572 --> 1:11:13.834
That's not my wife.

1:11:15.401 --> 1:11:17.925
I'm sorry?I said that's
not my wife.

1:11:17.969 --> 1:11:20.406
But it is
your ex-wife.

1:11:20.450 --> 1:11:22.930
Never seen that woman
before in my life.

1:11:25.063 --> 1:11:26.282
But your name
is Joyce?

1:11:26.630 --> 1:11:28.066
Uh...

1:11:28.109 --> 1:11:30.068
Well, it's a common name.[CHUCKLES LIGHTLY]

1:11:31.504 --> 1:11:32.766
'Course it is.Yeah.

1:11:34.551 --> 1:11:35.769
COMMISSIONER:
'Course it is.

1:11:38.076 --> 1:11:40.905
Well, Inspector,
in that case,
I believe

1:11:40.948 --> 1:11:42.472
you are owed
an apology.

1:11:44.778 --> 1:11:46.780
[GULPS] Constable.

1:11:48.521 --> 1:11:51.089
Uh... Yes, sir.
O' course.

1:11:51.132 --> 1:11:53.221
I'm...
I'm so sorry, sir.
I just...

1:11:53.265 --> 1:11:57.313
I just got the wrong end
of the stick, and I have
no excuse. I just...

1:11:57.356 --> 1:12:00.011
I jumped to conclusions again.
I'm so sorry.

1:12:05.364 --> 1:12:08.367
Commissioner, why don't you
run along back to the office,

1:12:08.411 --> 1:12:10.021
look over
the quarterly accounts.

1:12:10.064 --> 1:12:12.197
Let me handle
the murder investigation.

1:12:12.240 --> 1:12:13.372
Inspector.

1:12:16.680 --> 1:12:17.724
[WHISPERS] Sorry.

1:12:19.857 --> 1:12:21.989
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

1:12:52.411 --> 1:12:54.195
WOOLF: It's Dickie
and Sheila.

1:12:54.239 --> 1:12:57.198
DICKIE: Hello, Woolf.
Didn't expect
to see you here.

1:12:58.461 --> 1:13:01.115
[HUMMING]

1:13:01.159 --> 1:13:03.335
[DOORBELL RINGING]Perhaps, it is

1:13:03.379 --> 1:13:06.033
Miss Rams... bottom.
[MUMBLING]

1:13:06.077 --> 1:13:08.340
Get that... [SIGHS][DOORBELL CONTINUES RINGING]

1:13:15.173 --> 1:13:16.566
If you have
broken down,

1:13:16.609 --> 1:13:19.612
there is a garage
not 15 miles
from here.

1:13:19.656 --> 1:13:21.571
[CHUCKLES]
No, we're here
for dinner.

1:13:21.614 --> 1:13:23.311
I don't think so, sir.

1:13:23.355 --> 1:13:26.532
[CHUCKLES] This is
Winterbrook House?

1:13:26.576 --> 1:13:27.838
The Christie residence?

1:13:28.752 --> 1:13:29.883
It is.

1:13:29.927 --> 1:13:30.928
Uh, we have
an invitation.

1:13:30.971 --> 1:13:31.972
We do, yes.

1:13:33.974 --> 1:13:36.150
Richard Attenborough.
Friends call me "Dickie."

1:13:39.806 --> 1:13:41.591
[WIND WHISTLING]

1:13:44.028 --> 1:13:46.204
I do hope you haven't
traveled far.

1:13:50.208 --> 1:13:52.297
MAN: Fellowes!
Who is it?

1:13:52.340 --> 1:13:55.082
No one, sir. Tinkers.[FOOTSTEPS APPROACHING]

1:13:55.126 --> 1:13:57.389
MAN: What, in this
unseasonable blizzard?

1:13:57.433 --> 1:13:59.870
Come on, man.
Open sesame.

1:13:59.913 --> 1:14:01.741
Richard Attenborough.
Friends call me "Dickie."

1:14:01.785 --> 1:14:04.004
Max Mallowan,
eminent archaeologist.

1:14:04.048 --> 1:14:05.353
Good God, man,
you're frozen solid.

1:14:05.397 --> 1:14:06.877
It's cold.
It's cold, yes.Come in.

1:14:06.920 --> 1:14:08.879
Hello, Sheila Sim.
[CHUCKLES]Hello.

1:14:08.922 --> 1:14:10.533
John Woolf.How do you do?

1:14:10.576 --> 1:14:11.621
Ann Saville.

1:14:11.664 --> 1:14:13.536
We're friends of
Petula. Spencer.

1:14:13.579 --> 1:14:16.016
Oh, yes.
I know Choo.[CHUCKLES]

1:14:16.060 --> 1:14:18.671
We thought
we'd been invited
for dinner.

1:14:18.715 --> 1:14:21.239
Yes, we
received this,

1:14:21.282 --> 1:14:23.502
but apparently,
not from you.

1:14:23.546 --> 1:14:25.504
Extraordinary.

1:14:25.548 --> 1:14:28.289
You know who's going
to love this? Agatha.

1:14:28.333 --> 1:14:30.204
It's just like one
of her confections.

1:14:30.248 --> 1:14:31.423
She's in the kitchen now

1:14:31.467 --> 1:14:33.207
trying to figure out
some new ending.

1:14:33.251 --> 1:14:36.080
[SNICKERS] It helps
to do the dishes,
apparently.

1:14:36.123 --> 1:14:38.038
[ALL CHUCKLE]

1:14:39.779 --> 1:14:43.087
Ooh, hello.
Who else didn't
we invite to dinner?

1:14:43.130 --> 1:14:44.523
Ah, it's Petula.

1:14:44.567 --> 1:14:45.785
Why, so it is.

1:14:46.743 --> 1:14:48.222
Come in out of
the cold, Choo!

1:14:48.266 --> 1:14:49.920
What on Earth
have you got there?

1:14:51.095 --> 1:14:52.183
It's not Mother,
is it?

1:14:52.226 --> 1:14:53.619
PETULA: 'Fraid so.

1:14:54.011 --> 1:14:55.839
Oh, God.

1:14:55.882 --> 1:14:57.101
Better make that eight
for dinner, Fellowes,

1:14:57.144 --> 1:14:58.798
and let Agatha know.Yes, sir.

1:14:58.842 --> 1:15:00.060
And get a shovel
to clear the path.

1:15:00.104 --> 1:15:01.192
Yes, sir.

1:15:01.235 --> 1:15:02.323
And do we have
enough coal?

1:15:02.367 --> 1:15:04.021
Yes, sir.
Three bags full, sir.

1:15:04.064 --> 1:15:05.892
PETULA: Hello, Maxie.Hello, darling.

1:15:06.589 --> 1:15:08.721
Oh, it's a full house.

1:15:08.765 --> 1:15:10.027
[SHEILA CHUCKLES]Yes.

1:15:10.070 --> 1:15:11.376
Mother.

1:15:11.419 --> 1:15:13.204
Come on in.
Straight through
to the drawing room.

1:15:13.247 --> 1:15:14.640
PETULA: Here.MAX: Now,

1:15:14.684 --> 1:15:18.035
I have a rather potent
Mesopotamian aperitif

1:15:18.078 --> 1:15:19.906
that'll have you
thawed out
in a jiffy.

1:15:19.950 --> 1:15:20.994
[DOOR CLOSES]

1:15:21.038 --> 1:15:23.127
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:15:45.628 --> 1:15:48.239
I'm sorry again
that you had to
find out like this.

1:15:48.282 --> 1:15:50.676
Oh, I can't say
it came as a surprise.

1:15:51.677 --> 1:15:53.549
Leo was a bad seed.

1:15:54.375 --> 1:15:56.943
Always in trouble,
he was.

1:15:56.987 --> 1:15:58.902
He picked a fight
the night
he took us out.

1:15:58.945 --> 1:16:01.121
Mmm.
Mervyn Cocker-Norris
at the hotel.

1:16:01.948 --> 1:16:03.733
No. At the pictures.

1:16:04.081 --> 1:16:05.082
Oh.

1:16:13.438 --> 1:16:16.093
He turned
on this tall fella
who came in after us

1:16:16.136 --> 1:16:17.660
and shouted,

1:16:17.703 --> 1:16:19.575
"What are you
following me for,
buddy?"

1:16:20.314 --> 1:16:21.925
And, um...
[SCOFFS]

1:16:21.968 --> 1:16:23.274
Did he know
a good dentist,

1:16:23.317 --> 1:16:24.928
'cause he was
about to lose
a lot of teeth.

1:16:26.756 --> 1:16:27.800
Hmm.

1:16:27.844 --> 1:16:30.150
Right, who's ready
for a top-up?

1:16:30.194 --> 1:16:31.282
GUESTS: No.

1:16:31.325 --> 1:16:32.805
Where's
the old girl?

1:16:32.849 --> 1:16:34.807
Not gonna play
the recluse card,
is she?

1:16:34.851 --> 1:16:36.983
Oh, no, no, no.
She'll be down
soon enough.

1:16:37.027 --> 1:16:38.506
[CLATTERING UPSTAIRS]

1:16:39.333 --> 1:16:40.900
That will be Fellowes.

1:16:40.944 --> 1:16:42.423
The man's an oaf.

1:16:46.906 --> 1:16:49.126
A tall fella,
you say?JOYCE: Mmm.

1:16:49.909 --> 1:16:51.476
Had a funny accent.

1:16:53.304 --> 1:16:54.435
Italian?

1:16:54.479 --> 1:16:55.828
No, not that funny.

1:16:55.872 --> 1:16:57.090
More like...

1:16:59.092 --> 1:17:00.485
a village idiot.

1:17:01.442 --> 1:17:03.706
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC CONTINUES]

1:17:04.924 --> 1:17:06.404
I'm sorry,
but you have to
get out.

1:17:06.447 --> 1:17:07.579
[DOOR THUDS]

1:17:09.102 --> 1:17:11.975
Oh. No.
Good heavens.
No. Uh...

1:17:12.018 --> 1:17:14.064
Che cosa succede?[FUMBLING]

1:17:14.107 --> 1:17:15.456
Poli... Polizei.

1:17:15.500 --> 1:17:16.849
Telefono, por favor.

1:17:16.893 --> 1:17:18.285
Telefono?Yes. Si.

1:17:18.329 --> 1:17:19.722
Sta la. Gracias.

1:17:19.765 --> 1:17:22.289
[PHONE RINGS]

1:17:22.333 --> 1:17:24.552
Scotland Yard,
Sergeant Bakewell
speaking.

1:17:24.596 --> 1:17:25.684
Yes, Stoppard here.

1:17:31.168 --> 1:17:32.735
Police, stand back.

1:17:32.778 --> 1:17:34.650
He keeps a key...[STALKER GRUNTS]

1:17:34.693 --> 1:17:35.781
...under the mat.

1:17:36.608 --> 1:17:37.609
[PANTS]

1:17:40.481 --> 1:17:42.353
BAKEWELL: Let me guess,
Inspector.

1:17:42.396 --> 1:17:44.224
You're after
an address.

1:17:44.268 --> 1:17:45.356
How did you
know that?

1:17:45.399 --> 1:17:46.705
Constable Stalker, sir.

1:17:46.749 --> 1:17:48.576
She called just now
for the same information.

1:17:49.839 --> 1:17:50.883
Stalker?

1:17:58.325 --> 1:17:59.849
[WOMAN WHIMPERING]

1:17:59.892 --> 1:18:00.980
Agatha?

1:18:01.024 --> 1:18:02.460
Gosh, is she
all right?

1:18:02.503 --> 1:18:04.854
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC
INTENSIFYING]

1:18:29.530 --> 1:18:31.532
[MUSIC BUILDING UP]

1:18:34.057 --> 1:18:35.362
[MUSIC ENDS]

1:18:35.406 --> 1:18:37.234
Where's Agatha?
What have you done
with her?

1:18:45.068 --> 1:18:46.765
It was
the usher, sir.I know.

1:18:46.809 --> 1:18:48.419
He was under
our noses
all this time.

1:18:48.462 --> 1:18:50.638
Is he in?No, sir.
But I found this.

1:18:50.682 --> 1:18:52.075
If we get going now,
sir, we can...

1:18:52.118 --> 1:18:53.424
I can take it
from here,
Constable.

1:18:53.467 --> 1:18:54.947
Oh, right. And...
And me, sir?

1:18:54.991 --> 1:18:56.209
Go back
to the station.

1:18:57.471 --> 1:18:58.559
Yes, sir.

1:18:58.603 --> 1:18:59.735
Oh, and, Constable?

1:18:59.778 --> 1:19:01.345
Yes, sir?

1:19:01.388 --> 1:19:03.086
Make a start
on the paperwork.

1:19:05.131 --> 1:19:06.437
Yes, sir.[CAR DOOR CLOSES]

1:19:06.480 --> 1:19:08.221
[CAR DEPARTS]

1:19:11.050 --> 1:19:14.837
[PANTING]

1:19:17.143 --> 1:19:19.537
[UNNERVING MUSIC PLAYING]

1:19:19.580 --> 1:19:22.583
[SOFTLY] Is it me,
or does he look
awfully familiar?

1:19:22.627 --> 1:19:25.761
It's Dennis. He's an usher
from the Ambassadors

1:19:26.674 --> 1:19:28.372
Oh, Dennis!

1:19:28.415 --> 1:19:29.808
So nice
to see you.

1:19:29.852 --> 1:19:31.505
This is a strange
coincidence.

1:19:31.549 --> 1:19:32.593
What are you
doing here?

1:19:33.594 --> 1:19:34.770
Well, I invited you.

1:19:35.858 --> 1:19:37.511
Oh, my God.

1:19:37.555 --> 1:19:39.122
You killed Leo
and Mervyn!

1:19:39.905 --> 1:19:41.472
I did.

1:19:41.515 --> 1:19:43.996
I wanted to stop
the film and the play.

1:19:44.040 --> 1:19:45.693
What film?
What play?

1:19:45.737 --> 1:19:46.956
The Mousetrap![ALL GASP]

1:19:46.999 --> 1:19:48.305
Now, look here,
Dennis.

1:19:48.348 --> 1:19:50.829
We all have
strong opinions
on the theater.

1:19:50.873 --> 1:19:52.875
In a sense,
that's what
it's there for,

1:19:52.918 --> 1:19:54.920
to provoke emotion.

1:19:54.964 --> 1:19:57.749
And I appreciate
you don't care for
The Mousetrap.

1:19:57.793 --> 1:20:01.231
I'll be the first to admit
it's not exactly Hamlet.

1:20:01.274 --> 1:20:03.973
But you must see

1:20:04.016 --> 1:20:05.975
that this is
a bit of an
overreaction.

1:20:06.018 --> 1:20:07.846
That's not
what this is.

1:20:07.890 --> 1:20:10.762
Then, what...
what is this?

1:20:10.806 --> 1:20:13.330
It's not your story
to tell, is it?
It's mine.

1:20:13.373 --> 1:20:14.722
PETULA: Oh,
I might have known.

1:20:14.766 --> 1:20:16.072
A disgruntled
writer.

1:20:16.115 --> 1:20:18.552
Don't tell me,
you had
the idea first?

1:20:18.596 --> 1:20:20.903
No. It happened to me.

1:20:20.946 --> 1:20:22.208
I'm sorry, I am
completely lost.

1:20:22.252 --> 1:20:23.949
I don't have
a theatrical
background.

1:20:23.993 --> 1:20:26.343
You're not
Dennis Corrigan,
are you?

1:20:28.258 --> 1:20:29.259
[HUFFS]

1:20:30.521 --> 1:20:32.044
Oh, you poor boy.

1:20:32.871 --> 1:20:33.916
How do you mean?

1:20:33.959 --> 1:20:36.483
He lost his brother
in real life.

1:20:36.527 --> 1:20:38.485
Dreadful business,
it was.

1:20:38.529 --> 1:20:40.879
It was years ago, now.
I told you about it.

1:20:40.923 --> 1:20:43.142
It was the case
The Mousetrap
was based on.

1:20:43.186 --> 1:20:46.058
Inspired by, Mother.
And loosely.

1:20:46.102 --> 1:20:47.930
Oh, but you're
an usher.

1:20:47.973 --> 1:20:50.541
You had to
watch that play
night after night.

1:20:50.584 --> 1:20:52.108
It must've been
torture.

1:20:53.239 --> 1:20:55.938
I thought
it would help.

1:20:55.981 --> 1:20:57.896
He was only six
when he died,
my brother.

1:20:57.940 --> 1:21:00.768
The Mousetrapis
actually based on
a real-life case.

1:21:00.812 --> 1:21:03.075
DENNIS: Neglected
and left for dead
by the people

1:21:03.119 --> 1:21:05.556
who were supposed to
look after us.

1:21:05.599 --> 1:21:09.473
It sold a lot of newspapers,
but no one cared about us.

1:21:09.516 --> 1:21:11.649
[SLOW DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

1:21:11.692 --> 1:21:13.956
I thought the play
would be different.

1:21:13.999 --> 1:21:16.741
A famous writer was
going to tell our story.

1:21:16.784 --> 1:21:20.223
Two brothers
who put their faith in
the British social services.

1:21:20.266 --> 1:21:23.182
DENNIS: But when I saw
what Agatha Christie had done,

1:21:23.226 --> 1:21:27.056
used our pain and suffering
as a motive for
a deranged killer...

1:21:27.099 --> 1:21:28.709
[GASPS]

1:21:28.753 --> 1:21:30.886
...my brother's death
reduced to
a cheap sideshow...

1:21:30.929 --> 1:21:32.670
There's been
a murder?

1:21:32.713 --> 1:21:34.106
DENNIS: ...I knew
he wouldn't be able

1:21:34.150 --> 1:21:36.413
to rest in peace
until the play ended.

1:21:36.456 --> 1:21:38.981
But it didn't.

1:21:39.024 --> 1:21:42.071
It just went on,
and on, and on.

1:21:42.114 --> 1:21:44.508
The Mousetrapis 100,
not out.

1:21:44.551 --> 1:21:46.423
DENNIS: When I heard
about the film adaptation,

1:21:46.466 --> 1:21:48.512
I just snapped.

1:21:48.555 --> 1:21:51.254
Without me,
there is no movie.
You understand?

1:21:51.297 --> 1:21:52.690
You got
a problem, buddy?

1:21:52.733 --> 1:21:55.301
DENNIS: I killed the director
to stop the film,

1:21:55.345 --> 1:21:58.391
and thought
a corpse on the stage
would put an end to the play.

1:21:58.435 --> 1:22:00.263
[SCREAMS]

1:22:00.306 --> 1:22:02.308
But they didn't even close
the theater.

1:22:02.352 --> 1:22:03.919
Do you think
you might be
finished in time

1:22:03.962 --> 1:22:05.398
for curtain up
tomorrow night?

1:22:05.442 --> 1:22:07.270
DENNIS: And Mervyn's
new ideas for the film

1:22:07.313 --> 1:22:08.967
made me
sick to my stomach.

1:22:09.011 --> 1:22:10.621
I'll take
the bare bones
of the story,

1:22:10.664 --> 1:22:14.842
a rather mundane tale
of child abuse,
and make it my own.

1:22:14.886 --> 1:22:16.148
DENNIS: He left me
no choice.

1:22:16.192 --> 1:22:17.236
[GASPS]

1:22:17.280 --> 1:22:19.151
[SIGHS IN RELIEF]
You startled me.

1:22:19.195 --> 1:22:20.674
DENNIS: I had to
kill him, too.

1:22:21.110 --> 1:22:22.285
[CHOKING]

1:22:23.460 --> 1:22:25.853
I thought that would be
the end of it.

1:22:25.897 --> 1:22:28.247
But you all just carried on
like nothing had happened.

1:22:29.945 --> 1:22:31.207
Shame on you.[WOOLF WHIMPERS]

1:22:31.250 --> 1:22:33.165
[PETULA CLEARS THROAT]

1:22:33.209 --> 1:22:36.603
Well, maybe you'll
take notice if I kill
Agatha Christie herself.

1:22:38.649 --> 1:22:40.825
[MUFFLED GRUNTING]

1:22:40.868 --> 1:22:42.305
Oh, I think
she's tryin' to
say something.

1:22:42.348 --> 1:22:43.871
Oh, for God's sake,
let her out.

1:22:43.915 --> 1:22:44.960
I'll stop
the film.

1:22:45.003 --> 1:22:47.005
And the play.
This is barbaric.

1:22:47.049 --> 1:22:48.006
Fine.

1:22:49.399 --> 1:22:51.749
[ALL GASP]

1:22:52.924 --> 1:22:54.230
[SIGHS]

1:22:55.448 --> 1:22:57.320
WOOLF: Edana?

1:22:57.363 --> 1:22:59.496
Darling, what...
what are you
doing here?

1:22:59.539 --> 1:23:01.454
I followed you.

1:23:01.498 --> 1:23:03.500
I suppose
I was going to
make a scene.

1:23:03.543 --> 1:23:05.415
Hello, Ann.[ANN MUMBLES]

1:23:05.458 --> 1:23:08.984
Then this beanpole
assaulted me, and
I woke up in a carpet.

1:23:09.027 --> 1:23:11.769
If you're not
Agatha Christie,
where the hell is she?

1:23:11.812 --> 1:23:13.553
Good God, man.
You mean
you don't know?

1:23:13.597 --> 1:23:16.339
What kind of a bumbling,
half-witted psychopath
are you?

1:23:16.382 --> 1:23:18.384
Will you be quiet!
Please!

1:23:18.994 --> 1:23:20.821
Let me think!

1:23:20.865 --> 1:23:22.562
Yes, of course!
Of course.
Why don't you...

1:23:22.606 --> 1:23:25.522
Why don't you
come in and sit down,
Dennis? Um...

1:23:25.565 --> 1:23:27.263
PETULA: Yeah, yeah, yeah.

1:23:27.306 --> 1:23:29.700
Have a little moment
to yourself.

1:23:29.743 --> 1:23:31.397
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYS]

1:23:35.488 --> 1:23:37.403
[INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

1:23:47.979 --> 1:23:49.981
[MUSIC HALTS][WIND HOWLING]

1:23:51.287 --> 1:23:52.897
[ENGINE ROARING]

1:23:54.420 --> 1:23:56.335
[INTENSE MUSIC RESUMES]

1:24:10.045 --> 1:24:12.047
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:24:13.265 --> 1:24:14.223
[SIGHS]

1:24:25.234 --> 1:24:26.409
[MUSIC FADING]

1:24:27.105 --> 1:24:28.237
[SIGHS]

1:24:39.900 --> 1:24:40.901
[MOUTHING] What?

1:25:02.836 --> 1:25:05.535
Uh, well... Um...

1:25:05.578 --> 1:25:08.625
I, for one,
believe that, uh,

1:25:08.668 --> 1:25:11.062
Dennis here
is owed an apology.

1:25:11.106 --> 1:25:12.281
[ALL MURMUR IN AGREEMENT]MAX: Yes.

1:25:12.324 --> 1:25:14.457
SHEILA: He...
He's right,
of course.

1:25:14.500 --> 1:25:16.154
The truth
is the truth.

1:25:16.198 --> 1:25:19.070
It is not to be
manipulated
or played with,

1:25:19.114 --> 1:25:20.811
and certainly not
for entertainment.

1:25:20.854 --> 1:25:22.421
No, no.PETULA: No, no, no.

1:25:22.465 --> 1:25:24.771
SHEILA: Art is
supposed to
reveal the truth...

1:25:24.815 --> 1:25:25.816
ANN: Yes.GROUP: Yeah.

1:25:25.859 --> 1:25:27.905
SHEILA: ...not pervert it.

1:25:27.948 --> 1:25:30.125
How would
Agatha Christie
like it

1:25:30.168 --> 1:25:32.083
if someone took
one of her stories

1:25:32.127 --> 1:25:34.564
and twisted it
and corrupted it

1:25:34.607 --> 1:25:36.740
just for
the hell of it?
[CHUCKLES]

1:25:36.783 --> 1:25:38.829
[GROUP MURMURS]MAX: She wouldn't.

1:25:38.872 --> 1:25:41.266
I... I think that
we should all feel

1:25:41.310 --> 1:25:42.963
thoroughly ashamed
of ourselves.

1:25:43.007 --> 1:25:45.444
AGATHA: Oh, here we are.
Tea for everyone.

1:25:45.488 --> 1:25:46.706
MAX: There you are,
my dear.

1:25:46.750 --> 1:25:48.578
AGATHA: Sorry to
have kept you.

1:25:48.621 --> 1:25:50.580
No, no,
please don't get up,
not on my account.

1:25:51.189 --> 1:25:52.234
There, there.

1:25:52.277 --> 1:25:53.365
No, no, no,

1:25:53.409 --> 1:25:54.758
no, no, it's fine.Be careful.

1:25:54.801 --> 1:25:58.370
AGATHA: Just as it was.
I think it was that way.

1:25:58.414 --> 1:26:00.285
It is so nice to
see you again,
Agatha,

1:26:00.329 --> 1:26:01.678
in spite of
the circumstances.

1:26:01.721 --> 1:26:02.940
No, no, no,
not that one.

1:26:02.983 --> 1:26:04.855
No, that's for Dennis.
[CHUCKLES]

1:26:06.639 --> 1:26:08.119
[CUPS RATTLING]

1:26:08.163 --> 1:26:09.512
It is Dennis,
isn't it?

1:26:10.948 --> 1:26:12.471
There we are.

1:26:12.515 --> 1:26:15.170
I put an extra
lump in. [CHUCKLES]

1:26:15.213 --> 1:26:16.606
Thank you.

1:26:16.649 --> 1:26:18.738
Everyone else,
help themselves.

1:26:18.782 --> 1:26:19.957
[GROUP MURMURS][AGATHA SIGHS]

1:26:20.566 --> 1:26:22.525
Now, Dennis.

1:26:22.568 --> 1:26:23.787
How can I help?

1:26:23.830 --> 1:26:25.571
Why don't we sit here
and drink our tea

1:26:25.615 --> 1:26:28.531
and discuss the matter
like civilized people, hmm?

1:26:30.185 --> 1:26:32.230
I want you to stop
The Mousetrap.

1:26:32.274 --> 1:26:35.451
Oh, I am sorry,
but that
I cannot do. No.

1:26:35.494 --> 1:26:38.932
I'm afraid it goes against
everything I hold dear
in life.

1:26:38.976 --> 1:26:41.370
Yes. I'm a writer,
you see.

1:26:41.413 --> 1:26:44.721
I can't be told
what to write
or what not to write.

1:26:44.764 --> 1:26:47.637
It would be a denial
of one's freedom.

1:26:48.725 --> 1:26:52.685
Do you see, Dennis?
Hmm? Do drink up.

1:26:54.339 --> 1:26:56.602
[INTENSE MUSIC PLAYING]

1:27:18.058 --> 1:27:19.234
Oh, good God,
Fellowes.

1:27:20.974 --> 1:27:22.324
Get up. Get up.

1:27:22.367 --> 1:27:23.977
Now, look here,
young man, I...

1:27:24.021 --> 1:27:25.718
[GROUP GASPS]AGATHA: Max!

1:27:27.416 --> 1:27:29.244
[SCREAMS]

1:27:29.896 --> 1:27:31.507
[GLASS SHATTERS]

1:27:31.550 --> 1:27:32.986
[INTENSE MUSIC CONTINUES]

1:27:33.030 --> 1:27:34.031
[TIRE POPS]

1:27:35.380 --> 1:27:37.034
[TIRES SCREECHING]

1:27:47.131 --> 1:27:48.698
Yes, good idea... Oh.MAX: Yes.

1:27:48.741 --> 1:27:51.570
Oh, my God.
Now what's
happened?

1:27:51.614 --> 1:27:53.746
[SUSPENSEFUL MUSIC PLAYING]

1:28:07.064 --> 1:28:08.544
[AGATHA WHIMPERING]Oh.

1:28:09.632 --> 1:28:10.589
Dennis.

1:28:12.809 --> 1:28:15.115
Put the popular author
down, please, Dennis.

1:28:15.681 --> 1:28:16.943
No.[GROANS]

1:28:19.859 --> 1:28:21.078
[BOTTLE POPS OPEN]

1:28:21.121 --> 1:28:23.689
Sheila, darling,
now's hardly the time.

1:28:23.733 --> 1:28:25.648
SHEILA: Dickie,
I need a light.

1:28:25.691 --> 1:28:27.084
But you don't smoke.

1:28:27.867 --> 1:28:29.216
[WHISPERS] Dickie.

1:28:31.828 --> 1:28:33.743
[MUSIC INTENSIFYING]

1:28:39.792 --> 1:28:40.750
[AGATHA SCREAMS]

1:28:42.491 --> 1:28:43.709
[GROANING]

1:28:44.536 --> 1:28:46.233
[GUN CLICKING]

1:28:48.279 --> 1:28:49.280
[GRUNTING]

1:28:52.892 --> 1:28:55.068
[MUSIC BUILDING UP]

1:29:01.074 --> 1:29:02.685
[GUNSHOT][STALKER GRUNTS]

1:29:02.728 --> 1:29:04.513
[STOPPARD GROANS][GUN COCKS]

1:29:04.556 --> 1:29:05.601
STALKER: Look out!

1:29:06.993 --> 1:29:08.081
STOPPARD: No, Dennis!

1:29:08.125 --> 1:29:10.562
[GRUNTING]Don't do it, please!

1:29:11.258 --> 1:29:12.956
[AGATHA GRUNTS]

1:29:14.914 --> 1:29:16.481
[GROWLING]

1:29:16.525 --> 1:29:18.309
MAX: Darling!

1:29:18.353 --> 1:29:20.703
[AGATHA WHIMPERS]It's all right.

1:29:20.746 --> 1:29:22.879
He's dead.
It's over.

1:29:26.491 --> 1:29:27.449
Sir...

1:29:28.841 --> 1:29:29.929
I'm bleedin'.

1:29:33.150 --> 1:29:35.413
Hang in there,
Constable.

1:29:35.457 --> 1:29:37.546
Sergeant's exam's
in a month.

1:29:37.589 --> 1:29:39.765
It's funny, sir.
I actually...
I don't feel anything.

1:29:39.809 --> 1:29:41.245
I think it mighta
just been a nick.

1:29:41.288 --> 1:29:43.682
Yeah. Just the nick
of time, I'd say.

1:29:43.726 --> 1:29:45.118
[CHUCKLES]
Very good.

1:29:45.162 --> 1:29:48.470
[CHUCKLES]
I'm sorry,
Constable.

1:29:48.513 --> 1:29:50.646
I haven't been
altogether honest
or open

1:29:50.689 --> 1:29:53.475
or loyal
or fair to you
as a partner.

1:29:53.518 --> 1:29:57.653
Truth be told,
I haven't been a partner
at all, you know.

1:29:57.696 --> 1:29:58.915
Sir, you don't
have to say that.

1:29:58.958 --> 1:30:00.830
No, I want you
to know...

1:30:00.873 --> 1:30:02.266
I do trust you.

1:30:02.309 --> 1:30:04.529
Thank you, sir.
That does mean a lot.

1:30:04.573 --> 1:30:06.879
Um, but when I say
that I can't feel anything,

1:30:06.923 --> 1:30:09.578
I think what I mean
is that, um,

1:30:09.621 --> 1:30:12.058
I don't think
the bullet hit me, sir.

1:30:12.102 --> 1:30:13.146
What do you mean?

1:30:14.191 --> 1:30:15.410
Did you, um...

1:30:16.759 --> 1:30:18.848
STOPPARD: Oh, I see.STALKER: Oh, no. Yeah.

1:30:18.891 --> 1:30:20.893
Oh. Well, you're right
again, Constable.

1:30:20.937 --> 1:30:22.025
Are you
all right, sir?

1:30:22.068 --> 1:30:23.418
I think you better
call an ambulance.

1:30:23.461 --> 1:30:24.419
Yep.

1:30:25.985 --> 1:30:27.944
Yes, I don't feel
so good.

1:30:29.859 --> 1:30:32.122
A shoot-out
and a big explosion.

1:30:32.165 --> 1:30:35.299
Perhaps it's for the best
that Mervyn wasn't alive
to see it.

1:30:36.431 --> 1:30:37.432
Quite.

1:30:38.128 --> 1:30:40.435
[DRAMATIC MUSIC PLAYING]

1:31:07.113 --> 1:31:08.375
[MUSIC ENDS]

1:31:08.419 --> 1:31:11.117
It's okay, everyone,
I'm... I'm fine.

1:31:11.944 --> 1:31:16.296
[FOLK SONG PLAYING]

1:31:16.340 --> 1:31:20.475
LEO: Now that's what I call
a Leo Kopernick ending.

1:31:22.302 --> 1:31:24.783
But before we go
our separate ways,

1:31:24.827 --> 1:31:28.613
you'll be wanting to know
what became of
the heroes of this tale.

1:31:31.529 --> 1:31:33.792
Constable Stalker,
as advertised,

1:31:33.836 --> 1:31:37.535
sat her sergeant's exams
in the spring of 1953.

1:31:37.579 --> 1:31:40.277
[SONG CONTINUES PLAYING]

1:31:40.320 --> 1:31:41.974
She aced them.

1:31:44.150 --> 1:31:47.502
Detective Inspector
George Stoppard.

1:31:47.545 --> 1:31:49.721
LEO: Inspector Stoppard
was awarded

1:31:49.765 --> 1:31:53.203
the King's Police
and Fire Services Medal.

1:31:53.246 --> 1:31:54.465
COMMISSIONER: Oh.

1:31:54.509 --> 1:31:57.163
LEO: Harrold Scott
received a Knighthood.

1:31:57.207 --> 1:31:59.644
[CAMERA FLASHBULB POPPING]

1:32:00.863 --> 1:32:03.953
The play,
if you can believe it,

1:32:03.996 --> 1:32:08.044
is still going strong
in London's West End.

1:32:08.087 --> 1:32:12.091
Over 10 million people have
sat throughThe Mousetrap.

1:32:12.135 --> 1:32:13.789
TROTTER: Two brothers
who put their faith

1:32:13.832 --> 1:32:15.442
in the British
social services.

1:32:16.705 --> 1:32:19.969
A sorry tale of abuse
that ended in tragedy.

1:32:22.537 --> 1:32:24.843
Well, now that
you've seen our film,

1:32:24.887 --> 1:32:27.454
you are
an accomplice to murder.

1:32:27.498 --> 1:32:30.457
And so we ask you
to remember that it is
very much in your interest

1:32:30.501 --> 1:32:32.242
not to tell a soul
outside of this...

1:32:32.285 --> 1:32:34.374
Shh. Sir. Sorry.

1:32:34.418 --> 1:32:36.855
But I've missed
the endin' once.

1:32:36.899 --> 1:32:38.422
I don't wanna
miss it again.

1:32:38.465 --> 1:32:41.033
No, of course not.
I'm sorry. Sorry.

1:32:44.254 --> 1:32:45.647
[SHUSHES SOFTLY]

1:32:48.998 --> 1:32:50.173
[SONG ENDS]

1:32:51.043 --> 1:32:52.958
[UPBEAT MUSIC PLAYING]

1:34:14.561 --> 1:34:16.563
[JAZZ MUSIC PLAYING]
